# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sailing-ship
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] An **able seaman** (AB) is a seaman and member of the deck department of a merchant ship with more than two years' experience at sea and considered "well acquainted with his duty".
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] An AB may work as a watchstander, a day worker, or a combination of these roles.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] Once a sufficient amount of sea time is acquired, then the AB can apply to take a series of courses/examinations to become certified as an officer.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] At sea an AB watchstander's duties include standing watch as helmsman and lookout.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] A helmsman is required to maintain a steady course, properly execute all rudder orders and communicate using navigational terms relating to heading and steering.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] A watchstander may be called upon to stand security-related watches, such as a gangway watch or anchor watch while the ship is not underway.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] An AB dayworker performs general maintenance, repair, sanitation and upkeep of material, equipment, and areas in the deck department.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] This can include maintenance of the ship's metal structures such as chipping, scraping, cleaning, priming, and painting.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] Areas frequently in need of such maintenance include the hull, decks, superstructure, cargo gear, and smoke stack.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] Dayworkers also frequently perform maintenance on lifeboats, rescue boats and life rafts, and emergency and damage control gear.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] For many vessels, being a dayworker is a position granted to senior ABs, since it generally allows more time for rest and relaxation.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] An AB may be called on to use emergency, lifesaving, damage control, and safety equipment.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] Able seamen perform all operations connected with the launching of lifesaving equipment.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] An AB is expected to be able to operate deck machinery, such as the windlass or winches while mooring or unmooring, and to operate cargo gear.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] Able seamen require advanced training, including lifeboatman certification.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] The ship's boatswain, if carried, is typically a senior AB.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] The boatswain is in charge of the able seamen and ordinary seaman that comprise the unlicensed deck crew, and reports directly to the chief mate.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] *Able Seaman—Limited.* Requires 18 months service on deck in vessels of 100 gross tons or more which operate in a service not exclusively confined to the rivers and smaller inland lakes of the United States.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] *Able Seaman—Special.* Requires 12 months service on deck on vessels operating on the oceans, or the navigable waters of the United States including the Great Lakes.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] *Able Seaman—Special (OSV).* Requires six months service on deck on vessels operating on the oceans, or the navigable waters of the United States including the Great Lakes.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] *Able Seaman—Sail.* Requires six months service on deck on sail or auxiliary sail vessels operating on the oceans or the navigable waters of the United States including the Great Lakes.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] Time served in certain training programs and school ships may be substituted for the time of service listed above.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] 2. acquaintance with the practical handling of boats; including the ability to command the boat's crew.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] 5. knowledge of proper response to commands for handling the wheel and knowledge of the use of engine room telegraph or bell-pull signals.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] In 2004, studies indicate that a typical qualified Able Seaman (AB) sailing without an ITF contract might earn around $800 in total compensation; with an ITF contract total compensation is $1,300 per month.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] Some modern references claim that AB stands for *able-bodied seaman* as well as, or instead of, *able seaman.* *Able seaman* was originally entered using the abbreviation *AB* instead of the more obvious *AS* in ships' muster books or articles.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] Such an entry was likely to avoid confusion with ordinary seaman (*OS*).
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] Later the abbreviation began to be written as *A.B.*, leading to the folk-etymological *able-bodied seaman*.
[src:sailing-ship/able-seaman] The "correct" term, *able seaman,* remains in use in legal documents, in seaman's papers, and aboard ship.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] The **Act Prohibiting Importation of Slaves** of 1807 (2 Stat.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] 426, enacted March 2, 1807) is a United States federal law that prohibits the importation of slaves into the United States.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] It took effect on January 1, 1808, the earliest date permitted by the United States Constitution.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] This legislation was promoted by President Thomas Jefferson, who called for its enactment in his 1806 State of the Union address.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] He and others had promoted the idea since the 1770s.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] It reflected the general trend toward abolishing the international slave trade, which Virginia, followed by all the other states, had prohibited or restricted since then (South Carolina, however, had reopened its trade).
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Congress first regulated against the trade in the Slave Trade Act of 1794, which made it illegal for American ships to participate in the trade.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] The 1807 law took matters further by criminalizing all importation from abroad, even on foreign ships.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] The domestic slave trade within the United States was not affected by the 1807 law.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Indeed, with the legal supply of imported slaves terminated, the domestic trade increased in importance.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] In addition, some smuggling of slaves persisted.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] The Act affected only the import or export of slaves, and did not affect the internal trade in states or between states.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Georgia received transatlantic slave ships until 1798.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] South Carolina reopened the transatlantic slave trade in December 1803 and imported 39,075 enslaved people of African descent between 1804 and 1808).
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Article 1 Section 9 of the United States Constitution protected a state's involvement in the Atlantic slave trade for twenty years from federal prohibition.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Article 5 said that this clause could not be affected by constitutional amendment.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Only starting on January 1, 1808, could there be a federal law to abolish the international slave trade in all states, although individual states could and did ban it before such time.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] By 1775, Africans both free and enslaved made up 20% of the population in the Thirteen Colonies, which made them the second-largest ethnic group after English Americans.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] In 1774, the influential, revolutionary Fairfax Resolves, called for an end to the "wicked, cruel, and unnatural" Atlantic slave trade.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] During the Revolutionary War, the United Colonies all pledged to ban their involvement in the transatlantic slave trade.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] This was done for a variety of economic, political, and moral reasons depending on the colony.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] By 1807, only South Carolina allowed the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] On March 22, 1794, Congress passed the Slave Trade Act of 1794, which prohibited making, loading, outfitting, equipping or dispatching of any ship to be used in the trade of slaves, essentially limiting the trade to foreign ships.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] On August 5, 1797, John Brown of Providence, Rhode Island became the first American to be tried in federal court under the 1794 law.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Brown was convicted and was forced to forfeit his ship *Hope*.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] However, the same act also abolished the importation of slaves to the Mississippi Territory from "foreign parts" (foreign nations).
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] The penalty for illegally importing slaves from abroad to the territory was a fine of $300.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] In the Slave Trade Act of 1800, Congress outlawed U.S. citizens' investment in the trade and the employment of U.S. citizens on ships involved in the trade.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] On March 3, 1805, Joseph Bradley Varnum submitted a Massachusetts Proposition to amend the Constitution and Abolish the Slave Trade.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Under Varnum's leadership, legislation moved through Congress and passed both houses on March 2, 1807.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] President Thomas Jefferson signed the bill into law on March 2, 1807.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Many in Congress believed the act would doom slavery in the South, but they were mistaken.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] The role of the Navy was expanded to include patrols off the coasts of Cuba and South America.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] The effective date of the Act, January 1, 1808, was celebrated by Peter Williams, Jr., in "An Oration on the Abolition of the Slave Trade" delivered in New York City.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] While there are no exact figures known, historians estimate that up to 50,000 slaves were illegally imported into the United States after 1808, mostly through Spanish Florida and Texas, before those states were admitted to the Union.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] However, South Carolina Governor Henry Middleton estimated in 1819 that 13,000 smuggled African slaves arrived every year.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] In 1820, slave trading became a capital offense with an amendment to the 1819 Act to Protect the Commerce of the United States and Punish the Crime of Piracy.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] A total of 74 cases of slaving were brought in the United States between 1837 and 1860, "but few captains had been convicted, and those had received trifling sentences, which they had usually been able to avoid".
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Nathaniel Gordon, who was hanged in 1862, was the only person to be executed for illegal slave-trading in the United States.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] In addition, after the 1808 abolition of the slave trade to the United States, many Americans continued to engage in the slave trade by transporting Africans to Cuba.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] From 1808 to 1860, almost one-third of all slave ships either were owned by American merchants or were built and outfitted in American ports.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] It is possible that U.S. citizens "may have transported twice as many Africans to other countries such as Cuba and Brazil as they did to their own ports".
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Navy was slow to institute anti-slaving patrols off the slave ports of Africa—it was not until the 1820 legislation that authority was given to the president to use naval vessels for this task.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Even then, enforcement activity was sporadic and largely ineffective.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] The U.S. position meant that many slave ships from other countries falsely flew the American flag to avoid being seized by British anti-slaving patrols.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] The first U.S. warship sent to the African coast to intercept U.S. vessels operating in the illegal trade was the USS *Cyane*.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Navy ships were on station there in 1820 and 1821, arresting 11 American slavers.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] No further U.S. anti-slaving patrols were carried out until 1842, and then with limited effectiveness due to political pressure from the slave-owning states.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] The Atlantic slave trade was not ended until the U.S.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Civil War, when American-built and -managed ships were prevented from operating.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] In the South, the Fire-Eaters—antebellum pro-slavery extremists—proposed repealing the act and once more legalizing the international slave trade in the United States.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Historian Erskine Clarke writes that this call "was a shameless expression of their contempt for any antislavery sentiment and a part of their stratagem to divide the nation and create a slaveholding confederacy.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] The view alarmed even pro-slavery figures, such as former President John Tyler, who in retirement wrote a widely republished letter condemning the Fire-Eaters' call to abrogate Article 8 of the Webster–Ashburton Treaty (which barred the slave trade).
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Tyler noted that the South had voted to ratify the treaty.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Slavery and the cotton economy boomed during the 1850s, and cotton prices were resurgent after a decline in the 1840s.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] This, in turn, drove up the price of slaves, which led to further pressure to re-open the slave trade to meet demand or bring down prices.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Not all Southerners felt this way, however, as the high price of slaves benefitted slave owners and slave merchants.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] But the general sentiment called for a re-opening of the trade as a logical extension of the support for slavery.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Southerners reasoned that, if slavery was good, then putting more people into slavery must also be good, and that, if trading slaves in the South was okay, then trading them from Africa must also be okay.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Conventions of Southern planters repeatedly called for the trade to re-open.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] This, of course, was a non-starter in Congress.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] There were also attempts from state legislatures to allow the importation of "apprentices" from Africa, but without success.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] When trying to repeal the slave act failed, some turned to simply ignoring it.
[src:sailing-ship/act-prohibiting-importation-of-slaves] Notable cases during the 1850s included slaves smuggled aboard the *Wanderer* and the *Clotilda*.
[src:sailing-ship/aftcastle] The **aftercastle** (or **sterncastle**, sometimes **aftcastle**) is the stern structure behind the mizzenmast and above the transom on large sailing ships, such as carracks, caravels, galleons and galleasses.
[src:sailing-ship/aftcastle] It usually houses the captain's cabin and perhaps additional cabins and is crowned by the poop deck, which on men-of-war provided a heightened platform from which to fire upon other ships; it was also a place of defence in the event of boarding.
[src:sailing-ship/aftcastle] More common, but much smaller, is the forecastle.
[src:sailing-ship/aftcastle] The corresponding term *forecastle* today is also used to describe the upper deck of a sailing ship forward of the foremast in general.
[src:sailing-ship/aftcastle] As sailing ships evolved, the aftercastle gave way to the quarterdeck, whose span ran all the way to the main mast.
[src:sailing-ship/afterdeck] In naval architecture, an **afterdeck** or **after deck**, or sometimes the **aftdeck**, **aft deck** or **a-deck** is the open deck area toward the stern or aft back part of a ship or boat.
[src:sailing-ship/afterdeck] The afterdeck can be used for a number of different purposes, yet not all ships have an afterdeck.
[src:sailing-ship/afterdeck] In place of the afterdeck, a ship may be built with a poop deck, that is a deck that forms the roof of a cabin built in the rear, or "aft", part of the superstructure of a ship; a poop deck is usually higher up than an afterdeck.
[src:sailing-ship/afterdeck] A ship may have its superstructure or aftercastle located in the stern and thus not have an afterdeck.
[src:sailing-ship/afterdeck] The stern and afterdeck of a ship are usually more smooth and stable than the bow (front) of the ship in motion.
[src:sailing-ship/afterdeck] A taffrail is the handrail around the open afterdeck or poop deck.
[src:sailing-ship/afterdeck] On wooden sailing ships like man-of-war or East Indiaman the taffrail is usually a hand carved wood rail and often highly decorated.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] 1620), also known as the **Age of Exploration**, was part of the early modern period and overlapped with the Age of Sail.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It was a period from approximately the 15th to the 17th century, during which seafarers from European countries explored, colonized, and conquered regions across the globe.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Age of Discovery was a transformative period when previously isolated parts of the world became connected to form the world-system, and laid the groundwork for globalization.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The extensive overseas exploration, particularly the opening of maritime routes to the East Indies and European colonization of the Americas by the Spaniards and Portuguese, later joined by the English, French, and Dutch, spurred international global trade.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The interconnected global economy of the 21st century has its origins in the expansion of trade networks during this era.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The exploration created European colonial empires and marked an increased adoption of colonialism as a government policy in several European states.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] As such, it is sometimes synonymous with the first wave of European colonization.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] This colonization reshaped power dynamics causing geopolitical shifts in Europe and creating new centers of power beyond Europe.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Portuguese oceanic exploration began with maritime expeditions to the Macaronesian islands, including the Canary Islands, as well as Madeira and the Azores.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It continued with voyages along the coast of West Africa in 1434, and culminated in the establishment of a sea route to India in 1498 by Vasco da Gama, which initiated Portugal's maritime and commercial presence in Kerala and the Indian Ocean.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Spain also undertook other major early voyages, including the conquest of Mexico (1519–1521), the conquest of Peru (1532–1533), and the Manila galleon trade route (1565–1815), which linked the Americas and Asia across the Pacific.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] European exploration initiated the Columbian exchange between the Old World (Europe, Asia, and Africa) and New World (Americas).
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] This exchange involved the transfer of plants, animals, human populations (including slaves), communicable diseases, and culture across the Eastern and Western Hemispheres.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Age of Discovery and European exploration involved mapping the world, shaping a new worldview and facilitating contact with distant civilizations.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The continents drawn by European mapmakers developed from abstract "blobs" into the outlines more recognizable to us.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Simultaneously, the spread of new diseases, especially affecting American Indians, led to rapid declines in some populations.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The era saw widespread enslavement, exploitation and military conquest of Indigenous peoples, concurrent with the growing economic influence and spread of Western culture, science, and technology leading to a faster-than-exponential population growth world-wide.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The concept of discovery has been scrutinized, critically highlighting the history of the core term of this periodization.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The term "age of discovery" is in historical literature and still commonly used.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Something of which they had no prior knowledge had suddenly presented itself to their gaze." O'Gorman argues that the physical encounter with new territories was less important than the Europeans' effort to integrate this new knowledge into their worldview, what he calls "the invention of America".
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Pagden examines the origins of the terms "discovery" and "invention".
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In English, "discovery" and its forms in romance languages derive from "*disco-operio*, meaning to uncover, to reveal, to expose to the gaze", what was revealed existed previously.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Few Europeans during the period used the term "invention" for the European encounters, with the exception of Martin Waldseemüller, whose map first used the term "America".
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] A central legal concept of the discovery doctrine, expounded by the United States Supreme Court in 1823, draws on assertions of European powers' right to claim land during their explorations.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The concept of "discovery" has been used to enforce colonial claiming and discovery, but has been challenged by Indigenous peoples and researchers.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Many indigenous peoples have fundamentally challenged the concept of colonial claiming of "discovery" over their lands and people, as forced and negating indigenous presence.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The period alternatively called the *Age of Exploration*, has been scrutinized through reflections on the exploration.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Its understanding and use, has been discussed as being framed and used for colonial ventures, discrimination and exploitation, by combining it with concepts such as the frontier (as in Frontier Thesis) and manifest destiny, up to the contemporary age of space exploration.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Alternatively, the term *contact*, as in first contact, has been used to shed more light on the age of discovery and colonialism, using the alternative names of *Age of Contact* or *Contact Period*, discussing it as an "unfinished, diverse project".
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Portuguese began systematically exploring the Atlantic coast of Africa in 1418, under the sponsorship of Prince Henry the Navigator.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1488, Bartolomeu Dias reached the Indian Ocean by this route.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1492, the Catholic Monarchs of Spain funded Genoese mariner Christopher Columbus's (Italian: *Cristoforo Colombo*) plan to sail west to reach the Indies, by crossing the Atlantic.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus encountered a continent uncharted by Europeans (though it had been explored and temporarily colonized by the Norse 500 years earlier).
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Later, it was called America after Amerigo Vespucci, a trader working for Portugal.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal quickly claimed those lands under the terms of the Treaty of Alcáçovas, but Castile was able to persuade the Pope, who was Castilian, to issue four papal bulls to divide the world into two regions of exploration, where each kingdom had exclusive rights to claim newly discovered lands.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] These were modified by the Treaty of Tordesillas, ratified by Pope Julius II.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1498, a Portuguese expedition commanded by Vasco da Gama reached India by sailing around Africa, opening up direct trade with Asia.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Portuguese sailed further eastward, to the valuable Spice Islands in 1512, landing in China one year later.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Japan was reached by the Portuguese in 1543.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1513, Spanish explorer Vasco Núñez de Balboa crossed the Isthmus of Panama and reached the "other sea" from the New World.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Thus, Europe first received news of the eastern and western Pacific within a one-year span around 1512.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] East and west exploration overlapped in 1522, when a Spanish expedition sailing westward, led by Portuguese navigator Ferdinand Magellan (and, after his death in what is now the Philippines, by navigator Juan Sebastián Elcano), completed the first circumnavigation of the world.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Spanish *conquistadors* explored the interior of the Americas, and some of the South Pacific islands.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Their main objective was to disrupt Portuguese trade in the East.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1495, the French, English, and Dutch entered the race of exploration, after learning of Columbus' exploits, defying the Iberian monopoly on maritime trade by searching for new routes.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The first expedition was led by John Cabot in 1497 to the north, in the service of England, followed by French expeditions to South America and later to North America.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Later expeditions went to the Pacific Ocean around South America, and eventually by following the Portuguese around Africa, into the Indian Ocean; discovering Australia in 1606, New Zealand in 1642, and Hawaii in 1778.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 1580s to the 1640s, Russians explored and conquered almost the whole of Siberia, and claimed Alaska in the 1730s.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] After the fall of the Western Roman Empire largely severed the connection between Europe and lands further east, Christian Europe was largely a backwater compared to the Muslim world, which conquered and incorporated large territories in the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Christian Crusades to retake the Holy Land from the Muslims were not a military success, but they did bring Europe into contact with the Middle East and the valuable goods manufactured or traded there.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 12th century, the European economy was transformed by the interconnecting of river and sea trade routes.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Economic growth of Iberia followed the Christian reconquest of Al-Andalus in what is now southern Spain and the siege of Lisbon (1147 AD), in Portugal.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The decline of the Fatimid Caliphate's naval strength, which started before the First Crusade, helped the maritime Italian states, mainly Venice, Genoa and Pisa, dominate trade in the Eastern Mediterranean, with merchants there becoming wealthy and politically influential.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Norman conquest of England, in the late 11th century, allowed for peaceful trade on the North Sea.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Hanseatic League, a confederation of merchant guilds and their towns in north Germany, along the North Sea and Baltic Sea, was instrumental in the commercial development of the region.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In the 12th century, the regions of Flanders, Hainault, and Brabant produced the finest quality textiles in northwest Europe, which encouraged merchants from Genoa and Venice to sail there from the Mediterranean, through the Strait of Gibraltar, and up the Atlantic coast.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Nicolòzzo Spinola made the first recorded direct voyage from Genoa to Flanders in 1277.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Technological advancements that were important to the Age of Exploration were the adoption of the magnetic compass and advances in ship design.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass was an addition to the ancient method of navigation based on sightings of the sun and stars.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It was invented during the Chinese Han dynasty and had been used for navigation in China by the 11th century.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It was adopted by Arab traders in the Indian Ocean.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass spread to Europe by the late 12th or early 13th century.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Use of the compass for navigation in the Indian Ocean was first mentioned in 1232.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The first mention of use of the compass in Europe was in 1180.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Europeans used a "dry" compass, with a needle on a pivot.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass card was also a European invention.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The ships of the Age of Discovery post-dated the fusion of the northern European and Mediterranean shipbuilding traditions.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Prior to the late 13th/early 14th centuries, northern European ships were typically clinker built, with a single mast setting a square sail and a centre-line rudder hung on the sternpost with pintles and gudgeons.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Their counterparts in the Mediterranean were built with carvel hulls, had one or more masts (depending on size) which set lateen sails, and were steered with quarter-rudders positioned on the side of the hull.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Trade, pilgrimage and war brought ships from each tradition into the other's region, ultimately leading to the copying of features that were new to each.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Over the early 14th century, square sails started to be used in the Mediterranean, with the mainmast setting square rig and the mizzen carrying a lateen sail.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In the first two decades of the 15th century this arrangement was copied in northern Europe where, by the late 1430s, some ships were built with carvel hulls.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The result of this merging of traditions was the full-rigged ship, a carvel hull with a sternpost-hung pintle-and-gudgeon rudder and three masts: the foremast and mainmast setting square sails and the mizzen a lateen sail.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Alongside this type of vessel, the caravel was used.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] This type was also carvel built with a sternpost-hung rudder but could be completely lateen rigged or have some square sails.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Very few wrecks of Age of Discovery ships have been found and archaeologically investigated.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] More is known about Roman and Greek ships of classical antiquity than those of this period.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The caravel is particularly poorly understood, despite the number of "replicas" that have been constructed.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] However, a particular set of hull construction characteristics have been identified from wrecks of this time, referred to as Iberian Atlantic shipbuilding tradition.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] They are found in the Molasses Reef wreck, Highbourne Cay wreck, the Red Bay wreck and some sites in European waters.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] European medieval knowledge about Asia beyond the reach of the Byzantine Empire was sourced in partial reports, often obscured by legends, dating back from the conquests of Alexander the Great and successors.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Another source was the Radhanite Jewish trade networks of merchants established as go-betweens between Europe and the Muslim world during the time of the Crusader states.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] There were reports of great African Sahara, but the knowledge was limited for the Europeans, to the Mediterranean coast and little else, since the Arab blockade of North Africa precluded exploration inland.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Knowledge about the Atlantic African coast was fragmented and derived mainly from old Greek and Roman maps based on Carthaginian knowledge, including Roman exploration of Mauritania.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Red Sea was barely known and only trade links with the maritime republics, Venice especially, fostered the collection of accurate maritime knowledge.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Indian Ocean trade routes were sailed by Arab traders.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] By 1400, a Latin translation of Ptolemy's *Geographia* reached Italy from Constantinople.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The rediscovery of Roman geographical knowledge was a revelation, both for map-making and worldview, although reinforcing the idea that the Indian Ocean was landlocked.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] A prelude to the Age of Discovery was a series of European expeditions crossing Eurasia by land in the late Middle Ages.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Mongols had threatened Europe, but Mongol states also unified much of Eurasia and, from 1206 on, the *Pax Mongolica* allowed safe trade routes and communication lines from the Middle East to China.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The close Italian links to the Levant raised curiosity and commercial interest in countries which lay further east.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] There are a few accounts of merchants from North Africa and the Mediterranean, who traded in the Indian Ocean in late medieval times (see also Indo-Mediterranean § Medieval era).
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Christian embassies were sent as far as Karakorum during the Mongol invasions of the Levant, from which they gained a greater understanding of the world.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The first of these travellers was Giovanni da Pian del Carpine, dispatched by Pope Innocent IV to the Great Khan, who journeyed to Mongolia and back from 1241 to 1247.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Russian prince Yaroslav of Vladimir, and his sons Alexander Nevsky and Andrey II of Vladimir, travelled to the Mongolian capital.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Though having strong political implications, their journeys left no detailed accounts.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Other travellers followed, like French André de Longjumeau and Flemish William of Rubruck, who reached China through Central Asia.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Marco Polo, a Venetian merchant, dictated an account of journeys throughout Asia from 1271 to 1295, describing being a guest at the Yuan dynasty court of Kublai Khan in *Travels*.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Muslim fleet guarding the Strait of Gibraltar was defeated by Genoa in 1291.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In that year, the Genoese attempted their first Atlantic exploration when merchant brothers Vadino and Ugolino Vivaldi sailed from Genoa with two galleys, but disappeared off the Moroccan coast, feeding fears of oceanic travel.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1325 to 1354, a Moroccan scholar from Tangier, Ibn Battuta, journeyed through North Africa, the Sahara desert, West Africa, Southern Europe, Eastern Europe, the Horn of Africa, the Middle East, and Asia, having reached China.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] After returning, he dictated an account to a scholar he met in Granada, *The Rihla* ("The Journey"), the unheralded source on his adventures.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1357 and 1371, a book of supposed travels compiled by John Mandeville acquired popularity.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Despite the unreliable and often fantastical nature of its accounts, it was used as a reference for the East, Egypt, and the Levant in general, asserting the old belief that Jerusalem was the centre of the world.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Following the period of Timurid relations with Europe, in 1439, Niccolò de' Conti published an account of his travels as a Muslim merchant to India and Southeast Asia.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1466–1472, Russian merchant Afanasy Nikitin of Tver travelled to India, which he described in his book *A Journey Beyond the Three Seas*.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] These overland journeys had little immediate effect.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Mongol Empire collapsed almost as quickly as it formed and soon the route to the east became more difficult and dangerous.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Black Death of the 14th century also blocked travel and trade for a time.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Religion played a critical role in motivating European expansionism.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1487, Portuguese envoys Pero da Covilhã and Afonso de Paiva were sent on a covert mission to gather intelligence on a potential sea route to India and inquire about Prester John, a Nestorian patriarch and king, believed to rule over parts of the subcontinent.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Covilhã was warmly received upon his arrival in Ethiopia, but forbidden from leaving.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] During the Middle Ages, the spread of Christianity throughout Europe fueled the desire to sermonise in lands beyond.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] This evangelical effort became a significant part of the military conquests of European powers, like Portugal, Spain, and France, often leading to the conversion of indigenous peoples, voluntarily or forced.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Religious orders such as the Franciscans, Dominicans, Augustinians, and Jesuits partook in most missionary endeavours in the New World.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] By the late 16th and 17th centuries, the latter's presence increased as they sought to reassert their power and revive the Catholic culture of Europe, which had been damaged by the Reformation.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Chinese had wide connections through trade in Asia and been sailing to Arabia, East Africa, and Egypt since the Tang dynasty (AD 618–907).
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1405 and 1421, the third Ming emperor Yongle sponsored long range tributary missions in the Indian Ocean under the command of admiral Zheng He.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] A large fleet of new junk ships was prepared for the international diplomatic expeditions.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The largest of these junks—that the Chinese termed *bao chuan* (treasure ships)—may have measured 121 metres (397 ft), and thousands of sailors were involved.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] At least seven well-documented expeditions were launched, each bigger and more expensive than the last.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The fleets visited Arabia, East Africa, India, Malay Archipelago, and Thailand (then called Siam), exchanging goods along the way.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] They presented gifts of gold, silver, porcelain, and silk; in return, received such novelties as ostriches, zebras, camels, ivory, and giraffes.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] After the emperor's death, Zheng He led a final expedition departing from Nanking in 1431 and returning to Beijing in 1433.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It is likely this last expedition reached as far as Madagascar.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The travels were reported by Ma Huan, a Muslim voyager and translator who accompanied Zheng He on three of the expeditions, his account published as the *Yingya Shenglan* (Overall Survey of the Ocean's Shores) (1433).
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The voyages had a significant and lasting effect on the organization of a maritime network, using and creating nodes and conduits in its wake, thereby restructuring international and cross-cultural relationships and exchanges.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It was especially impactful as no other polity had exerted naval dominance over all sectors of the Indian Ocean, prior to these voyages.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Ming promoted alternative nodes as a strategy to establish control over the network.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] For instance, due to Chinese involvement, ports such as Malacca (in Southeast Asia), Cochin (Malabar Coast), and Malindi (Swahili Coast) had grown as key alternatives to other established ports.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The appearance of the Ming treasure fleet generated and intensified competition among contending polities and rivals, each seeking an alliance with the Ming.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The expeditions developed into a maritime trade enterprise, with imperial control over local markets and court-monitored transactions, generating revenue for China and its partners.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] They boosted regional trade and production, caused a supply shock in Eurasia and led to price spikes in Europe in the early 15th century.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The tributary relations promoted during the voyages manifested a trend toward cross-regional interconnections and early globalization in Asia and Africa.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Diplomatic relations were built on mutually beneficial maritime trade and China's strong naval presence in foreign waters, with Chinese naval superiority being a key factor in these interactions.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The voyages brought about the Western Ocean's regional integration and increase in international circulation of people, ideas, and goods.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It provided a platform for cosmopolitan discourses, which took place in locations such as the ships of the Ming treasure fleet, the Ming capitals of Nanjing as well as Beijing, and the banquet receptions organized by the Ming court for foreign representatives.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Diverse groups of people from maritime countries congregated, interacted, and traveled together as the treasure fleet sailed from and to China.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] For the first time, the maritime region from China to Africa was under the dominance of a single imperial power and allowed for the creation of a cosmopolitan space.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] These long-distance journeys were not followed up, as the Ming dynasty retreated in the *haijin*, a policy of isolationism, having limited maritime trade.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 8th until the 15th century, the Republic of Venice and neighboring maritime republics held the monopoly of European trade with the Middle East.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The silk and spice trade, involving spices, incense, herbs, drugs, and opium, made these Mediterranean city-states phenomenally rich.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Spices were among the most expensive and demanded products of the Middle Ages, as they were used in medieval medicine, religious rituals, cosmetics, perfumery, and food additives and preservatives.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] They were imported from Asia and Africa.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Muslim traders dominated maritime routes throughout the Indian Ocean, tapping source regions in the Far East and shipping for trading emporiums in India, mainly Calicut, westward to Hormuz in the Persian Gulf and Jeddah in the Red Sea.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] From there, overland routes led to the Mediterranean.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Afterwards, the routes into Asia through the Black Sea and through Armenia and Persia became blocked by wars and banditry as the Mongol states disintegrated.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The trade route from the Persian Gulf to the Mediterranean by land is also dangerous due to the unstable territorial control of the Mamluk.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The trade from India went almost entirely into the Red Sea.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Nevertheless, European spices have not become more expensive as a result.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Forced to reduce activity in the Black Sea, and at war with Venice, the Genoese had turned to North African trade of wheat, olive oil and a search for silver and gold.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Europeans had a constant deficit in silver and gold, as it only went out, spent on eastern trade now cut off.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Several European mines were exhausted, The lack of bullion led to the development of a complex banking system to manage the risks in trade (the first state bank, *Banco di San Giorgio*, was founded in 1407 at Genoa).
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Sailing into the ports of Bruges and England, Genoese communities were then established in Portugal, who profited from their enterprise and financial expertise.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] European sailing had been primarily close to land cabotage, guided by portolan charts.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] These charts specified proven ocean routes guided by coastal landmarks: sailors departed from a known point, followed a compass heading, and tried to identify their location by its landmarks.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] For the first oceanic exploration Europeans used the compass, and advances in cartography and astronomy.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Arab navigational tools like the astrolabe and quadrant were used for celestial navigation.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Muslim lands in Asia were more economically developed, had better infrastructure, despite Europe's economic changes brought by the Black Death, allowing for more freedoms.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Islamic gunpowder empires concealed knowledge from European Christian traders about where lucrative locations such as Indonesia were.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1317, King Denis of Portugal made an agreement with Genoese merchant sailor Manuel Pessanha, appointing him first admiral of the Portuguese Navy, to defend the country against Muslim pirate raids.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Outbreaks of bubonic plague led to depopulation in the second half of the 14th century: only the sea offered alternatives, with most population settling in fishing and trading coastal areas.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1325 and 1357, Afonso IV of Portugal encouraged maritime commerce and ordered the first explorations.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Canary Islands, already known to the Genoese, were claimed as officially discovered under the patronage of the Portuguese, but in 1344, Castile disputed them.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] To ensure their trade monopoly, Europeans, beginning with the Portuguese, attempted to install a Mediterranean system of trade which used military intimidation, to divert trade through ports they controlled; there it could be taxed.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1415, Ceuta, in North Africa, was conquered by the Portuguese aiming to control navigation of the African coast.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Young prince Henry the Navigator became aware of profit possibilities in the trans-Saharan trade routes.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] For centuries slave and gold trade routes linking West Africa with the Mediterranean passed over the Western Sahara Desert, controlled by the Moors.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] He invested in sponsoring voyages down the coast of Mauritania, gathering merchants, shipowners and stakeholders interested in new sea lanes.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Soon the Atlantic islands of Madeira (1419) and the Azores (1427) were reached.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The expedition leader who established settlements on Madeira, was explorer João Gonçalves Zarco.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Europeans did not know what lay beyond Cape Non (Cape Chaunar) on the African coast, and whether it was possible to return once crossed.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Nautical myths warned of monsters or an edge of the world, but Henry's navigation challenged such beliefs: starting in 1421, systematic sailing overcame it, reaching the difficult Cape Bojador that in 1434 one of Henry's captains, Gil Eanes, finally passed.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1440, caravels were extensively used for the exploration of the coast of Africa.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] This was an Iberian ship type, used for fishing, commerce and military purposes.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It had a sternpost-mounted rudder, a shallow draft helpful in exploring coastlines, a good sailing performance, with a windward ability.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The lateen rig was less useful when sailing downwind – which explains Christopher Columbus (Italian: *Cristoforo Colombo*) re-rigging the *Niña* with square rig.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] For celestial navigation the Portuguese used the ephemerides, which experienced a remarkable diffusion in the 15th century.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] These were astronomical charts plotting the location of the stars.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Published in 1496 by Jewish astronomer and mathematician Abraham Zacuto, the Almanac Perpetuum included some of these tables for the movements of stars.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] These revolutionized navigation, allowing the calculation of latitude.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Exact longitude remained elusive from mariners for centuries.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Using the caravel, systematic exploration continued southerly, advancing one degree a year.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Senegal and Cape Verde Peninsula were reached in 1445 and in 1446, Álvaro Fernandes pushed on almost as far as present-day Sierra Leone.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1453, the fall of Constantinople to the Ottomans was a perceived blow to Christendom and established business links with the East.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The king, who had been inquiring of Genoese experts about a seaway to India, commissioned the Fra Mauro world map, which arrived in Lisbon in 1459.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1456, Diogo Gomes reached the Cape Verde archipelago.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In the next decade captains at the service of Prince Henry, discovered the remaining islands which were occupied during the 15th century.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Gulf of Guinea was reached in the 1460s.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1460, Pedro de Sintra reached Sierra Leone.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Prince Henry died in November after which, given the meagre revenues, exploration was granted to Lisbon merchant Fernão Gomes in 1469, who in exchange for the monopoly of trade in the Gulf of Guinea had to explore 100 miles (161 kilometres) each year for five years.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] With his sponsorship, explorers João de Santarém, Pedro Escobar, Lopo Gonçalves, Fernão do Pó, and Pedro de Sintra made it beyond those goals.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] They reached the Southern Hemisphere and islands of the Gulf of Guinea, including São Tomé and Príncipe and Elmina in 1471.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] There, in what came to be called the "Gold Coast", in today's Ghana, a thriving alluvial gold trade was found among the natives, Arab and Berber traders.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1478, during the War of the Castilian Succession, near the coast at Elmina a large battle was fought between a Castilian armada of 35 caravels, and a Portuguese fleet for the hegemony of the Guinea trade.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The war ended with a Portuguese victory, followed by official recognition by the Catholic Monarchs of Portuguese sovereignty over most of the disputed West African territories embodied in the Treaty of Alcáçovas, 1479.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1481, João II decided to build São Jorge da Mina factory.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1482, the Congo River was explored by Diogo Cão, who in 1486 continued to Cape Cross (modern Namibia).
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The next crucial breakthrough was in 1488, when Bartolomeu Dias rounded the southern tip of Africa, which he named Cabo das Tormentas, "Cape of Storms", then sailing east as far as the mouth of the Great Fish River, proving the Indian Ocean was accessible from the Atlantic.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Pero da Covilhã, sent out travelling secretly overland, had reached Ethiopia having collected important information about the Red Sea and Quenia coast, suggesting a sea route to the Indies would soon be forthcoming.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Soon the cape was renamed by King John II of Portugal the *Cape of Good Hope*, because of the optimism engendered by the possibility of a sea route to India, proving false the view that had existed since Ptolemy that the Indian Ocean was land-locked.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Based on later stories of the phantom island known as Bacalao and the carvings on Dighton Rock some have speculated that Portuguese explorer João Vaz Corte-Real discovered Newfoundland in 1473, but the sources are considered unreliable.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal's Iberian rival, Castile, had begun to establish its rule over the Canary Islands in 1402, but became distracted by internal Iberian politics and the repelling of Islamic invasion attempts through most of the 15th century.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Following the unification of the crowns of Castile and Aragon, an emerging modern Spain became committed to the search for new trade routes overseas.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Crown of Aragon had been an important maritime power, controlling territories in eastern Spain, southwestern France, major islands like Sicily, Malta, and the Kingdom of Naples and Sardinia, with mainland possessions as far as Greece.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1485 and 1488, Columbus had presented the project to king John II of Portugal, who rejected it.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] On 3 August 1492, Columbus departed from Palos de la Frontera.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Land was sighted on 12 October, and Columbus called the island *San Salvador* (Guanahani now in The Bahamas), in what he thought to be the East Indies.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus explored the north coast of Cuba and Hispaniola, by 5 December.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] He was received by the native cacique Guacanagari, who gave him permission to leave some men behind.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus left 39 and founded the settlement of *La Navidad* in what is now Haiti.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Before returning to Spain, he kidnapped 10-25 natives.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Only 7-8 of the 'Indians' arrived alive, but they made an impression on Seville.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] On 15 March 1493, he arrived in Barcelona, where he reported to Isabella and Ferdinand.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Word of his discovery of new lands spread throughout Europe.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus and other Spanish explorers were initially disappointed with their discoveries—unlike Africa or Asia, the Caribbean islanders had little to trade.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The islands thus became the focus of colonization efforts.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It was not until the continent was explored that Spain found the wealth it had sought.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Shortly after Columbus's return from what would be called the "West Indies", a division of influence became necessary to avoid conflict between the Spaniards and Portuguese.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It did not mention Portugal, which could not claim newly discovered lands east of the line.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] King John II of Portugal was displeased with the arrangement, feeling it gave him too little land—preventing him from reaching India, his goal.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] He negotiated directly with Ferdinand and Isabella to move the line west, allowing him to claim newly discovered lands east of it.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1494, the Treaty of Tordesillas divided the world between Portugal and Spain.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal gained control over Africa, Asia, and eastern South America (Brazil), encompassing everything outside Europe east of a line drawn 370 leagues west of the Cape Verde islands.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Spaniards received everything west of this line, including the islands discovered by Columbus on his first voyage.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The dividing line, situated about halfway between Portuguese Cape Verde and Spanish discoveries in the Caribbean, split the known world of Atlantic islands evenly.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1500, Pedro Álvares Cabral, initially considering the Brazilian coast as a large island, claimed it for Portugal east of the dividing line.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] This claim was acknowledged by the Spaniards.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral, heading towards India, followed a corridor in the Atlantic negotiated by the treaty for favorable winds.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Later the Spanish territory would prove to include huge areas of the continental mainland of North and South America, though Portuguese-controlled Brazil would expand across the line, and settlements by other European powers ignored the treaty.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Little of the divided area had actually been seen by Europeans, as it was only divided by a geographical definition rather than control on the ground.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The desire to compete with the Ottoman Empire and Columbus's first voyage spurred further maritime exploration and, from 1497, other explorers headed west.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] That year John Cabot (Italian: *Giovanni Caboto*), also a commissioned Italian, got letters patent from King Henry VII of England.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Sailing from Bristol Cabot crossed the Atlantic from a northerly latitude hoping the voyage to the "West Indies" would be shorter and made landfall in North America, possibly Newfoundland.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Prior to Cabot's voyage, the furthest European expeditions in the North Atlantic had been by Norse explorers, who established settlements in Newfoundland and Greenland, which were abandoned in the 11th century and mid-15th century, respectively.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Merchants from Bristol had sponsored exploratory voyages in the 1480s, which did not report anything of note.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1499, João Fernandes Lavrador was licensed by the King of Portugal and together with Pero de Barcelos they first sighted Labrador, which was granted and named after him.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1499 and 1502, the brothers Gaspar and Miguel Corte Real explored and named the coasts of Greenland and Newfoundland.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Both explorations are noted in the 1502 Cantino planisphere.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1497, newly crowned King Manuel I of Portugal sent an exploratory fleet eastwards, fulfilling his predecessor's project of finding a route to the Indies.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In July 1499, news spread that the Portuguese had reached the "true Indies", as a letter was dispatched by the Portuguese king to the Spanish Monarchs.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The third expedition by Columbus in 1498 was the beginning of the first successful Spanish colonization in the West Indies, on the island of Hispaniola.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Despite growing doubts, Columbus refused to accept he had not reached the Indies.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] He discovered the mouth of the Orinoco River on the north coast of South America and thought the huge quantity of fresh water coming from it could only be from a continental land mass, which he was certain was Asia.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] As shipping between Seville and the West Indies grew, knowledge of the Caribbean islands, Central America and the northern coast of South America increased.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] One of these Spanish fleets, that of Alonso de Ojeda and Amerigo Vespucci in 1499–1500 reached land at the coast of what is now Guyana, where the two seem to have separated in opposite directions.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci sailed southward, discovering the mouth of the Amazon River in July 1499, and reaching 6°S, in present-day north east Brazil, before turning around.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Vicente Yáñez Pinzon was blown off course and reached what is now the northeast coast of Brazil on 26 January 1500, exploring as far south as the present-day state of Pernambuco.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] His fleet was the first to fully enter the Amazon River estuary, which he named *Saint Mary's River of the Freshwater Sea*.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The land was too far east for the Castilians to claim under the Treaty of Tordesillas, but the discovery created Castilian interest, with a second voyage by Pinzon in 1508 (the Pinzón–Solís voyage) and a voyage in 1515–1516 by a navigator of the 1508 expedition, Juan Díaz de Solís.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The 1515–1516 expedition was spurred on by reports of Portuguese exploration of the region.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It ended when de Solís and some of his crew disappeared when exploring the River Plata in a boat, but what they found reignited Spanish interest, and colonization began in 1531.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In April 1500, the second Portuguese India Armada, headed by Pedro Álvares Cabral, with a crew of expert captains, encountered the Brazilian coast as it swung westward in the Atlantic while performing a large volta do mar to avoid becalming in the Gulf of Guinea.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] On 21 April, a mountain was seen and named *Monte Pascoal*, and on 22 April Cabral landed.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] On 25 April, the entire fleet sailed into the harbour they named *Porto Seguro*.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral perceived that the new land lay east of the line of Tordesillas, and sent an envoy to Portugal with the discovery in letters, including the letter of Pero Vaz de Caminha.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Believing the land to be an island, he named it Ilha de Vera Cruz.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] From the east coast, the fleet then turned eastward towards the southern tip of Africa and India.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral was the first captain to touch four continents, leading the first expedition that connected and united Europe, Africa, the New World, and Asia.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] At the invitation of King Manuel I of Portugal, Amerigo Vespucci participated as an observer in the exploratory voyages to the east coast of South America.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It was understood that Columbus had not reached Asia but found a new continent, the Americas.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Americas were named in 1507 by cartographers Martin Waldseemüller and Matthias Ringmann, after Amerigo Vespucci.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1501 to 1502, one of these Portuguese expeditions, led by Gonçalo Coelho, sailed south along the coast of South America to the bay of present-day Rio de Janeiro.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci's account states that the expedition reached the latitude "South Pole elevation 52° S", in the "cold" latitudes of what is now southern Patagonia, before turning back.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci wrote that they headed toward the southwest and south, following "a long, unbending coastline", apparently coincident with the southern South American coast.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] This seems controversial, since he changed part of his description in the subsequent letter, stating a shift, from about 32° S (Southern Brazil) to the south-southeast, to open sea, maintaining that they reached 50°/52° S.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1503, Binot Paulmier de Gonneville, challenging the Portuguese policy of *mare clausum*, led one of the earliest French Normand and Breton expeditions to Brazil.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] He intended to sail to the East Indies, but near the Cape of Good Hope, his ship was diverted to the west by a storm, and landed in the present-day state of Santa Catarina (southern Brazil), on 5 January 1504.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1511 to 1512, Portuguese captains João de Lisboa and Estevão de Fróis reached the River Plata estuary in present-day Uruguay and Argentina, and went as far south as the present-day Gulf of San Matias at 42°S.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The expedition reached a cape extending north to south which they called Cape of "Santa Maria" (Punta del Este); and after 40°S they found a "Cape" or "a point or place extending into the sea", and a "Gulf".
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] After they had navigated for nearly 300 km (186 mi) to round the cape, they again sighted the continent on the other side and steered towards the northwest, but a storm prevented them from making headway.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Driven away by the *Tramontane* or north wind, they retraced their course.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Christopher de Haro, a Fleming of Sephardic origin, who would serve the Spanish Crown after 1516, believed the navigators had discovered a southern *strait* to west and Asia.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1519, an expedition sent by the Spanish Crown to find a way to Asia was led by the experienced Portuguese navigator Ferdinand Magellan.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The fleet explored the rivers and bays as it charted the South American coast, until it found a way to the Pacific Ocean through the Strait of Magellan.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1524 to 1525, Aleixo Garcia, a Portuguese conquistador, led a private expedition of shipwrecked Castilian and Portuguese adventurers, who recruited about 2,000 Guaraní Indians.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] They explored the territories of present-day southern Brazil, Paraguay, and Bolivia, using the native trail network, the *Peabiru*.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] They were the first Europeans to cross the Chaco and reach the outer territories of the Inca Empire on the hills of the Andes.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Protected from direct Spanish competition by the Treaty of Tordesillas, Portuguese eastward exploration and colonization continued apace.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Twice, in 1485 and 1488, Portugal officially rejected Genoese Christopher Columbus's idea of reaching India by sailing westwards.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] King John II of Portugal's experts rejected it, for they held the opinion that Columbus's estimation of a travel distance of 2,400 miles (3,860 km) was low, and in part because Bartolomeu Dias departed in 1487 trying the rounding of the southern tip of Africa.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They believed that sailing east would require a far shorter journey.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Dias's return from the Cape of Good Hope in 1488, and Pero da Covilhã's travel to Ethiopia overland indicated that the richness of the Indian Ocean was accessible from the Atlantic.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In July 1497, a small exploratory fleet of four ships and about 170 men left Lisbon under the command of Vasco da Gama.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] By December the fleet passed the Great Fish River—where Dias had turned back—and sailed into waters unknown to the Europeans.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Sailing into the Indian Ocean, da Gama entered a maritime region that had three different and well-developed trade circuits.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The one da Gama encountered connected Mogadishu on the east coast of Africa; Aden, at the tip of the Arabian peninsula; the Persian port of Hormuz; Cambay, in northwestern India; and Calicut, in southwestern India.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 20 May 1498, they arrived at Calicut.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The efforts of Vasco da Gama to get favorable trading conditions were hampered by the low value of their goods, compared with the valuable goods traded there.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Two years and two days after departure, Gama and a survivor crew of 55 men returned in glory to Portugal as the first ships to sail directly from Europe to India.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Da Gama's voyage is romanticized in the Os Lusíadas, an epic poem by fellow discovery-era traveler Luís de Camões.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The poem is widely regarded as Portugal's greatest literary achievement.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1500, a second, larger fleet of thirteen ships and about 1500 men were sent to India.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Under the command of Pedro Álvares Cabral, they made the first landfall on the Brazilian coast, giving Portugal its claim.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Later, in the Indian Ocean, one of Cabral's ships reached Madagascar (1501), which was partly explored by Tristão da Cunha in 1507; Mauritius was discovered in 1507, Socotra occupied in 1506.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In the same year Lourenço de Almeida landed in Sri Lanka, the eastern island named "Taprobane" in remote accounts of Alexander the Great's and 4th-century BC Greek geographer Megasthenes.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On the Asiatic mainland, the first factories (trading-posts) were established at Kochi and Calicut (1501) and then Goa (1510).
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The Portuguese continued sailing eastward from India, entering a second existing circuit of the Indian Ocean trade, from Calicut and Quillon in India, to Southeast Asia, including Malacca and Palembang.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1511, Afonso de Albuquerque conquered Malacca for Portugal, then the center of Asian trade.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] East of Malacca, Albuquerque sent several diplomatic missions: Duarte Fernandes as the first European envoy to the Kingdom of Siam (modern Thailand).
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Learning the location of the so-called "spice islands", heretofore a secret from the Europeans, were the Spice Islands, mainly the Banda, then the world's only source of nutmeg and cloves.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Reaching these was the main purpose for the Portuguese voyages in the Indian Ocean.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Albuquerque sent an expedition led by António de Abreu to Banda (via Java and the Lesser Sunda Islands), where they were the first Europeans to arrive in early 1512, after taking a route through which they also reached first the islands of Buru, Ambon, and Seram.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In May 1513, Jorge Álvares, one of the Portuguese envoys, reached China.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Fernão Pires de Andrade visited Canton in 1517 and opened up trade with China.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After a few decades, hostilities between the Portuguese and Chinese ceased and in 1557 the Chinese allowed the Portuguese to occupy Macau.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] To enforce a trade monopoly, Muscat and Hormuz in the Persian Gulf were seized by Afonso de Albuquerque in 1507 and in 1515, respectively.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] He also entered into diplomatic relations with Persia.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1513, while trying to conquer Aden, an expedition led by Albuquerque cruised the Red Sea inside the Bab al-Mandab and sheltered at Kamaran island.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1521, a force under António Correia conquered Bahrain, ushering in a period of almost 80 years of Portuguese rule of the Gulf archipelago.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In the Red Sea, Massawa was the most northerly point frequented by the Portuguese until 1541, when a fleet under Estevão da Gama penetrated as far as Suez.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1513, about 40 miles (64 kilometres) south of Acandí, in present-day Colombia, Spanish Vasco Núñez de Balboa heard unexpected news of an "other sea" rich in gold, which he received with great interest.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] With few resources and using information given by *caciques*, he journeyed across the Isthmus of Panama with 190 Spaniards, a few native guides, and a pack of dogs.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Balboa, using a brigantine and ten native canoe, explored the coast, facing battles and dense jungles.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 25 September, after crossing the Chucunaque River mountains, he became the first European to see the Pacific Ocean from the New World.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition briefly navigated the Pacific, naming the bay *San Miguel* and the sea *Mar del Sur* (South Sea).
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Seeking gold, Balboa traversed cacique lands to the islands, naming the largest Isla Rica (now Isla del Rey) and the group *Archipiélago de las Perlas*, names still in use today.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1515 to 1516, the Spanish fleet led by Juan Díaz de Solís sailed down the east coast of South America as far as Río de la Plata, which Solís named shortly before he died while trying to find a passage to the "South Sea".
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] By 1516, several Portuguese navigators conflicting with King Manuel I of Portugal gathered in Seville to serve the newly crowned Charles I of Spain.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Among them were explorers Diogo and Duarte Barbosa, Estêvão Gomes, João Serrão, and Ferdinand Magellan, cartographers Jorge Reinel and Diogo Ribeiro, cosmographers Francisco and Ruy Faleiro and the Flemish merchant Christopher de Haro.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Ferdinand Magellan had sailed in India for Portugal up to 1513, when the Spice Islands were reached, and had kept contact with Francisco Serrão who was living there.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Magellan developed the theory that the Spice Islands were in the Tordesillas Spanish area, based on studies by Faleiro brothers.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Aware of the efforts of the Spanish to find a route to India by sailing west, Magellan presented his plan to Charles I of Spain.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The king and Christopher de Haro financed Magellan's expedition.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] A fleet was put together, and Spanish navigators such as Juan Sebastián Elcano joined the enterprise.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 10 August 1519, they departed from Seville with a fleet of five ships—the caravel flagship *Trinidad* under Magellan's command, and carracks *San Antonio*, *Concepcion*, *Santiago* and *Victoria*.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They contained a crew of about 237 European men from several regions, with the goal of reaching the Spice Islands by travelling west, trying to reclaim it under Spain's economic and political sphere.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The fleet sailed south, avoiding Portuguese Brazil, and became the first to reach Tierra del Fuego.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Starting on 21 October, they navigated the 373-mile (600 km) Strait of Magellan, entering the Pacific on 28 November, which Magellan named Mar Pacífico for its calm waters.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After crossing the Pacific, Magellan was killed in the Battle of Mactan in the Philippines.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Juan Sebastián Elcano completed the voyage, reaching the Spice Islands in 1521.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 6 September 1522, the *Victoria* returned to Spain, completing the first circumnavigation of the globe.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Of the original crew, only 18 men completed the circumnavigation; 17 returned later, including twelve captured by the Portuguese and five survivors of the Trinidad.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Antonio Pigafetta, a Venetian scholar, kept a detailed journal that is a key source of information about the voyage.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] This round-the-world voyage gave Spain valuable knowledge of the world and its oceans which later helped in the exploration and settlement of the Philippines.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Soon after Magellan's expedition, the Portuguese rushed to seize the surviving crew and built a fort in Ternate.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1525, Charles I of Spain sent another expedition westward to colonize the Spice Islands, claiming that they were in his zone of the Treaty of Tordesillas.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The fleet of seven ships and 450 men was led by García Jofre de Loaísa and included the most notable Spanish navigators: Juan Sebastián Elcano and Loaísa, who died then, and the young Andrés de Urdaneta.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Near the Strait of Magellan one of the ships was pushed south by a storm, reaching 56° S, where they thought seeing "*earth's end*": so Cape Horn was crossed for the first time.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition reached the islands with great difficulty, docking at Tidore.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The conflict with the Portuguese established in nearby Ternate was inevitable, starting nearly a decade of skirmishes.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] As there was not a set eastern limit to the Tordesillas line, both kingdoms organized meetings to resolve the issue.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1524 to 1529, Portuguese and Spanish experts met at Badajoz-Elvas trying to find the exact location of the antimeridian of Tordesillas, which would divide the world into two equal hemispheres.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Each crown appointed three astronomers and cartographers, three pilots, and three mathematicians.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Lopo Homem, Portuguese cartographer and cosmographer was on the board, along with cartographer Diogo Ribeiro of the Spanish delegation.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The board met several times without reaching an agreement: the knowledge at that time was insufficient for an accurate calculation of longitude, and each group gave the islands to its sovereign.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The issue was settled only in 1529, after a long negotiation, with the signing of Treaty of Zaragoza, which allocated the Spice Islands to Portugal and the Philippines to Spain.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1525 to 1528, Portugal sent several expeditions around the Spice Islands.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Gomes de Sequeira and Diogo da Rocha were sent north by the governor of Ternate Jorge de Menezes, being the first Europeans to reach the Caroline Islands, which they named *Islands of Gomes de Sequeira*.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1526, Jorge de Meneses docked on Biak and Waigeo islands, Papua New Guinea.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Based on these explorations stands the theory of Portuguese discovery of Australia, one among several competing theories about the early discovery of Australia, supported by Australian historian Kenneth McIntyre, stating it was discovered by Cristóvão de Mendonça and Gomes de Sequeira.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1527, Hernán Cortés fitted out a fleet to find new lands in the "South Sea" (Pacific Ocean), asking his cousin Álvaro de Saavedra Cerón to take charge.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 31 October 1527, Saavedra sailed from New Spain, crossing the Pacific and touring the north of New Guinea, then named *Isla de Oro*.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In October 1528, one of the vessels reached the Spice Islands.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In his attempt to return to New Spain he was diverted by the northeast trade winds, which threw him back, so he tried sailing back down, to the south.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] He returned to New Guinea and sailed northeast, where he sighted the Marshall Islands and the Admiralty Islands, but again was surprised by the winds, which brought him a third time to the Moluccas.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] This westbound return route was hard to find but was eventually discovered by Andrés de Urdaneta in 1565.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Rumors of undiscovered islands northwest of Hispaniola reached Spain by 1511, ushering King Ferdinand's interest in forestalling further exploration.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] While the Portuguese were making huge gains in the Indian Ocean, the Spanish invested in exploring inland in search of gold and other valuable resources.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The members of these expeditions, the conquistadors, were not soldiers in an army, but more like soldiers of fortune; they came from a variety of backgrounds including artisans, merchants, clergy, lawyers, lesser nobility and a few freed slaves.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They usually supplied their own equipment or were extended credit to purchase it in exchange for a share in profits.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They usually had no professional military training, but a number of them had previous experience on other expeditions.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In the Americas, the Spanish encountered large indigenous empires and formed alliances with indigenous people through small expeditions.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After establishing Spanish sovereignty and discovering wealth, the crown focused on implementing Spanish state and church institutions.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] A key element was the 'spiritual conquest' through Christian evangelization.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The initial economy relied on a tribute and forced labor under the *encomienda* system.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The discovery of vast silver deposits transformed both the colonial economies of Mexico and Peru and Spain's economy.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] With global trade networks and valuable American crops, Spain's economy strengthened, enhancing its status as a world power.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] During this time, pandemics of European diseases such as smallpox decimated the indigenous populations.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1512, to reward Juan Ponce de León for exploring Puerto Rico in 1508, King Ferdinand urged him to seek these new lands.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] He would become governor of discovered lands but was to finance himself all exploration.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] With three ships and about 200 men, Léon set out from Puerto Rico in March 1513.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In April, they sighted land and named it *La Florida*—because it was Easter (Florida) season—believing it was an island, becoming credited as the first European to land in the continent.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The arrival location has been disputed between St.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Augustine, Ponce de León Inlet and Melbourne Beach.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They headed south for further exploration and on 8 April encountered a current so strong that it pushed them backward: this was the first encounter with the Gulf Stream that would soon become the primary route for eastbound ships leaving the Spanish Indies bound for Europe.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They explored down the coast reaching Biscayne Bay, Dry Tortugas and then sailing southwest in an attempt to circle Cuba to return, reaching Grand Bahama on July.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1517, Cuba's governor Diego Velázquez de Cuéllar commissioned a fleet under the command of Hernández de Córdoba to explore the Yucatán Peninsula.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They reached the coast where Mayans invited them to land.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They were attacked at night and only a remnant of the crew returned.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Velázquez then commissioned another expedition led by his nephew Juan de Grijalva, who sailed south along the coast to Tabasco, part of the Aztec Empire.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1518, Velázquez gave the mayor of the capital of Cuba, Hernán Cortés, the command of an expedition to secure the interior of Mexico but, due to an old gripe between them, revoked the charter.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In February 1519, Cortés went ahead anyway, in an act of open mutiny.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] With about 11 ships, 500 men, 13 horses, and a small number of cannons he landed in Yucatán, in Mayan territory, claiming the land for the Spanish crown.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] From Trinidad he proceeded to Tabasco and won a battle against the natives.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Among the vanquished was Marina (La Malinche), his future mistress, who knew both (Aztec) Nahuatl language and Maya, becoming a valuable interpreter and counsellor.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In July, his men took over Veracruz and he placed himself under direct orders of new king Charles I of Spain.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] There Cortés asked for a meeting with Aztec emperor Moctezuma II, who repeatedly refused.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They headed to Tenochtitlan and on the way made alliances with several tribes.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In October, accompanied by about 3,000 Tlaxcaltec they marched to Cholula, the second largest city in central Mexico.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Either to instill fear upon the Aztecs waiting for him or (as he later claimed) wishing to make an example when he feared native treachery, they massacred thousands of unarmed members of the nobility gathered at the central plaza and partially burned the city.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 8 November, Cortés and his large army were welcomed by Moctezuma II in Tenochtitlan, who hoped to learn about them to eventually defeat them.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Moctezuma gave lavish gifts, which led Cortés to plunder the city.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés claimed the Aztecs saw him as an emissary or incarnation of the god Quetzalcōātl, though this is contested by few historians.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Upon learning that his men had been attacked on the coast, Cortés took Moctezuma hostage in his palace, demanding tribute for King Charles.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Meanwhile, Velasquez sent another expedition, led by Pánfilo de Narváez, to oppose Cortès, arriving in Mexico in April 1520 with 1,100 men.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés left 200 men in Tenochtitlan and took the rest to confront Narvaez, whom he overcame, convincing his men to join him.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In Tenochtitlán, one of Cortés's lieutenants committed a massacre in the Great Temple, triggering local rebellion.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés speedily returned, attempting the support of Moctezuma but the Aztec emperor was killed, possibly stoned by his subjects.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The Spaniards fled for Tlaxcala during the *Noche Triste*, where they managed a narrow escape while their back guard was massacred.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Much of the treasure looted was lost during this panicked escape.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After a battle in Otumba they reached Tlaxcala, having lost 870 men.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Having prevailed with the assistance of allies and reinforcements from Cuba, Cortés besieged Tenochtitlán and captured its ruler Cuauhtémoc in August 1521.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] As the Aztec Empire ended, he claimed the city for Spain and renamed it Mexico City.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] A first attempt to explore western South America was undertaken in 1522 by Pascual de Andagoya.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Native South Americans told him about a gold-rich territory on a river called Pirú.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Having reached San Juan River (Colombia), Andagoya fell ill and returned to Panama, where he spread the news about "Pirú" as the legendary El Dorado.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] These, along with the accounts of the success of Hernán Cortés, caught the attention of Pizarro.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Francisco Pizarro had accompanied Balboa in the crossing of the Isthmus of Panama.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1524, he formed a partnership with priest Hernando de Luque and soldier Diego de Almagro to explore the south, agreeing to divide the profits.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They dubbed the enterprise the "*Empresa del Levante*": Pizarro would command, Almagro would provide military and food supplies, and Luque would be in charge of finances and additional provisions.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 13 September 1524, the first of three expeditions set out to conquer Peru with 80 men and 40 horses.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The venture failed, halting in Colombia due to bad weather, hunger, and conflicts with locals; Almagro lost an eye.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Their route was marked by *Puerto Deseado* (desired port), *Puerto del Hambre* (port of hunger), and *Puerto quemado* (burned port).
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Two years later, a second expedition began with reluctant permission from the Governor of Panama.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In August 1526, they departed with two ships, 160 men, and horses.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Upon reaching the San Juan River, Pizarro explored swampy coasts, while Almagro sought reinforcements.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's pilot, sailing south and crossing the equator, captured a raft from Tumbes.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] To his surprise, the raft carried coveted textiles, ceramics, gold, silver, and emeralds, becoming the expedition's main focus.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Almagro later joined with reinforcements, and despite challenging conditions, they reached Atacames, where a sizable native population under Inca rule was observed, though they did not land.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro, safe near the coast, sent Almagro and Luque for reinforcements with proof of the rumoured gold.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The new governor rejected a third expedition, ordering everyone back to Panama.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Almagro and Luque seized the chance to rejoin Pizarro.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] At *Isla de Gallo*, Pizarro drew a line, presenting the choice between Peru's riches and Panama's poverty.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Thirteen men, The Famous Thirteen, stayed and headed to *La Isla Gorgona*, staying seven months until provisions arrived.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They sailed south and by April 1528, reached northwestern Peru's Tumbes region, warmly received by the *Tumpis*.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's men reported incredible riches, llama sightings, and the natives named them "Children of the Sun" for their fair complexion and brilliant armour.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They decided to return to Panama to prepare a final expedition, sailing south through named territories like Cabo Blanco, port of Payta, Sechura, Punta de Aguja, Santa Cruz, and Trujillo, reaching the ninth degree south.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In the spring of 1528, Pizarro sailed for Spain, where he had an interview with king Charles I.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The king heard of his expeditions in lands rich in gold and silver and promised to support him.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The *Capitulación de Toledo* authorized Pizarro to proceed with the conquest of Peru.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro was then able to convince many friends and relatives to join: his brothers Hernándo Pizarro, Juan Pizarro, Gonzalo Pizarro, and also Francisco de Orellana, who would later explore the Amazon River, as well as his cousin Pedro Pizarro.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's third and final expedition left Panama for Peru on 27 December 1530.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] With three ships and one hundred and eighty men, they landed near Ecuador and sailed to Tumbes, finding the place destroyed.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They entered the interior and established the first Spanish settlement in Peru, San Miguel de Piura.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] One of the men returned with an Incan envoy and an invitation for a meeting.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Since the last meeting, the Inca had begun a civil war and Atahualpa had been resting in northern Peru following the defeat of his brother Huáscar.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After marching for two months, they approached Atahualpa.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] He refused the Spanish, saying he would be "no man's tributary".
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] There were fewer than 200 Spanish to his 80,000 soldiers, but Pizarro attacked and won against the Incan army in the Battle of Cajamarca, taking Atahualpa captive at the so-called Ransom Room.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite fulfilling his promise of filling one room with gold and two with silver, he was convicted for killing his brother and plotting against Pizarro, and was executed.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After the Spanish had sealed the conquest of Peru, Jauja in fertile Mantaro Valley was established as Peru's provisional capital, but it was too far up in the mountains, and Pizarro founded the city of Lima on 18 January 1535, which Pizarro considered one of the most important acts in his life.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1543, three Portuguese traders accidentally became the first Westerners to reach and trade with Japan.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] According to Fernão Mendes Pinto, who claimed to be in this journey, they arrived at Tanegashima, where the locals were impressed by firearms that would be immediately made by the Japanese on a large scale.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The Spanish conquest of the Philippines was ordered by Philip II of Spain, and Andrés de Urdaneta was the designated commander.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Urdaneta agreed to accompany the expedition but refused to command and Miguel López de Legazpi was appointed instead.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition set sail in November 1564.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After spending some time on the islands, Legazpi sent Urdaneta back to find a better return route.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Urdaneta set sail from San Miguel on the island of Cebu on 1 June 1565, but was obliged to sail as far as 38 degrees North latitude to obtain favorable winds.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] He reasoned that the trade winds of the Pacific might move in a gyre as the Atlantic winds did.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] If in the Atlantic, ships made the *Volta do mar* to pick up winds that would bring them back from Madeira, then, he reasoned, by sailing far to the north before heading east, he would pick up trade winds to bring him back to North America.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] His hunch paid off, and he hit the coast near Cape Mendocino, California, then followed the coast south.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The ship reached the port of Acapulco, on 8 October 1565, having traveled 12,000 miles (19,000 kilometres) in 130 days.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Fourteen of his crew died; only Urdaneta and Felipe de Salcedo, nephew of López de Legazpi, had strength enough to cast the anchors.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Thus, a cross-Pacific Spanish route was established, between Mexico and the Philippines.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] For a long time, these routes were used by the Manila galleons, thereby creating a trade link joining China, the Americas, and Europe via the combined trans-Pacific and trans-Atlantic routes.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] European nations outside Iberia did not recognize the Treaty of Tordesillas between Portugal and Castile, nor did they recognize Pope Alexander VI's donation of the Spanish finds in the New World.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] France, the Netherlands, and England each had a long maritime tradition and had been engaging in privateering.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite Iberian protections, the new technologies and maps soon made their way north.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After the marriage of Henry VIII of England and Catherine of Aragon failed to produce a male heir and Henry failed to obtain a papal dispensation to annul his marriage, he broke with the Roman Catholic Church and established himself as head of the Church of England.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] This added religious conflict to political conflict.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] When much of The Netherlands became Protestant, it sought political and religious independence from Catholic Spain.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1568, the Dutch rebelled against the rule of Philip II of Spain leading to the Eighty Years' War.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The war between England and Spain also broke out.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1580, Philip II became King of Portugal, as heir to its Crown.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Although he ruled Portugal and its empire as separate from the Spanish Empire, the union of the crowns produced a Catholic superpower, which England and the Netherlands challenged.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In the eighty-year Dutch War of Independence, Philip's troops conquered the important trading cities of Bruges and Ghent.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Antwerp, then the most important port in the world, fell in 1585.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The Protestant population was given two years to settle affairs before leaving the city.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Those were mainly skilled craftsmen, rich merchants of the port cities and refugees that fled religious persecution, particularly Sephardic Jews from Portugal and Spain and, later, the Huguenots from France.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The Pilgrim Fathers also spent time there before going to the New World.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] This mass immigration was an important driving force: a small port in 1585, Amsterdam quickly transformed into one of the most important commercial centres in the world.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After the failure of the Spanish Armada in 1588, there was a huge expansion of maritime trade even though the defeat of the English Armada would confirm the naval supremacy of the Spanish navy over the emergent competitors.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch maritime power rose quickly as Dutch sailors, skilled in navigation and mapmaking, engaged with Portuguese voyages.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1592, Cornelis de Houtman gathered information on the Spice Islands in Lisbon.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The same year, Jan Huyghen van Linschoten published a detailed travel report in Amsterdam, providing navigation instructions for reaching the East Indies and Japan.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Following this, Houtman led the Dutch's first exploratory voyage, discovering a new route from Madagascar to the Sunda Strait and securing a treaty with the Banten Sultan.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The Dutch also demonstrated their maritime strength by seizing Malacca from Portugal in 1641, following a series of battles that began in 1602.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch and British interest, fed on new information, led to a movement of commercial expansion, and the foundation of English (1600) and Dutch (1602) chartered companies.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch, French, and English sent ships which flouted the Portuguese monopoly, concentrated mostly on the coastal areas, which proved unable to defend against such a vast and dispersed venture.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The 1497 English expedition authorized by Henry VII of England was led by Italian Venetian John Cabot (Giovanni Caboto); it was the first of a series of French and English missions exploring North America.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Mariners from the Italian peninsula played an important role in early explorations, most especially Genoese mariner Christopher Columbus.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] With its major conquests of central Mexico and Peru and discoveries of silver, Spain put limited efforts into exploring the northern part of the Americas; its resources were concentrated in Central and South America where more wealth had been found.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] These other European expeditions were initially motivated by the same idea as Columbus, namely a westerly shortcut to the Asian mainland.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After the existence of "another ocean" (the Pacific) was confirmed by Balboa in 1513, there still remained the motivation of potentially finding an oceanic Northwest Passage for Asian trade.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] This was not discovered until the early twentieth century, but other possibilities were found, although nothing on the scale of the spectacular ones of the Spanish.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In the early 17th century colonists from a number of Northern European states began to settle on the east coast of North America.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1524, Italian Giovanni da Verrazzano sailed under the authority of Francis I of France, who was motivated by indignation over the division of the world between Portuguese and Spanish.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Verrazzano explored the Atlantic Coast of North America, from South Carolina to Newfoundland, and was the first recorded European to visit what would later become the Virginia Colony and the United States.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In the same year Estêvão Gomes, a Portuguese cartographer who had sailed in Ferdinand Magellan's fleet, explored Nova Scotia, sailing South through Maine, where he entered what is now New York Harbor, the Hudson River and eventually reached Florida in August 1525.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] As a result of his expedition, the 1529 Diogo Ribeiro world map outlines the East coast of North America almost perfectly.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Europeans explored the Pacific Coast beginning in the mid-16th century.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Spaniard Francisco de Ulloa explored the Pacific coast of present-day Mexico including the Gulf of California, proving that Baja California was a peninsula.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite his report based on first-hand information, the myth persisted in Europe that California was an island.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] His account provided the first recorded use of the name "California".
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] João Rodrigues Cabrilho, a Portuguese navigator sailing for the Spanish Crown, was the first European to set foot in California, landing on 28 September 1542, on the shores of San Diego Bay and claiming California for Spain.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] He also landed on San Miguel, one of the Channel Islands, and continued as far north as Point Reyes on the mainland.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After his death, the crew continued exploring as far north as Oregon.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The English privateer Francis Drake sailed along the coast in 1579 north of Cabrillo's landing site while circumnavigating the world.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake had a long and largely successful career attacking Spanish settlements in the Caribbean islands and the mainland so for the English, he was a great hero and fervent Protestant, but for the Spanish, he was "a frightening monster".
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake played a major role in the defeat of the Spanish Armada in 1588 but led an armada himself to the Spanish Caribbean that was unsuccessful in dislodging the Spanish.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 5 June 1579, the ship briefly made first landfall at South Cove, Cape Arago, just south of Coos Bay, Oregon, and then sailed south while searching for a suitable harbor to repair his damaged ship.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 17 June, Drake and his crew found a protected cove when they landed on the Pacific coast of what is now Northern California near Point Reyes.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] While ashore, he claimed the area for Queen Elizabeth I of England as Nova Albion or New Albion.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] To document and assert his claim, Drake posted an engraved plate of brass to claim sovereignty for Queen Elizabeth and her successors on the throne.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake's landfalls on the west coast of North America are one small part of his 1577–1580 circumnavigation of the globe, the first captain of his own ship to do so.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake died in 1596 off the coast of Panama, following injuries from a raid.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] He explored the Hudson River and laid the foundation for Dutch colonization of the region.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Hudson's final expedition ranged farther north in search of the Northwest Passage, leading to his discovery of the Hudson Strait and Hudson Bay.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After wintering in James Bay, Hudson tried to press on with his voyage in the spring of 1611, but his crew mutinied and they cast him adrift.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] France, the Netherlands, and England sought a sea route to Asia after finding none through Africa or South America.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] With no route through the Americas, they focused on northern passages, driving European exploration of the Arctic coasts.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The idea of a link between the Atlantic and Pacific was first proposed by Russian diplomat Gerasimov in 1525, though Russian Pomors had explored parts of the route as early as the 11th century.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1553, English explorer Hugh Willoughby with chief pilot Richard Chancellor were sent out with three vessels in search of a passage by London's Company of Merchant Adventurers to New Lands.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] During the voyage across the Barents Sea, Willoughby thought he saw islands to the north, and islands called Willoughby's Land were shown on maps published by Plancius and Mercator into the 1640s.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The vessels were separated by "terrible whirlwinds" in the Norwegian Sea and Willoughby sailed into a bay near the present border between Finland and Russia.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] His ships with the frozen crews, including Captain Willoughby and his journal, were found by Russian fishermen a year later.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Richard Chancellor was able to drop anchor in the White Sea and make his way overland to Moscow and Ivan the Terrible's court, opening trade with Russia and the Company of Merchant Adventurers became the Muscovy Company.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In June 1576, English mariner Martin Frobisher led an expedition consisting of three ships and 35 men to search for a north-west passage around North America.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The voyage was supported by the Muscovy Company, the same merchants that hired Hugh Willoughby to find a northeast passage above Russia.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Violent storms sank one ship and forced another to turn back but Frobisher and the remaining ship reached the coast of Labrador in July.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] A few days later they came upon the mouth of what is now Frobisher Bay.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Frobisher believed it to be the entrance to a north-west passage and named it Frobisher's Strait and claimed Baffin Island for Queen Elizabeth.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After some preliminary exploration, Frobisher returned to England.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] He commanded two subsequent voyages in 1577 and 1578 but failed to find the hoped-for passage.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Frobisher brought to England his ships laden with ore, but it was found to be worthless and damaged his reputation as an explorer.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] He remains an important early historical figure in Canada.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 5 June 1594, Dutch cartographer Willem Barentsz departed from Texel in a fleet of three ships to enter the Kara Sea, with the hopes of finding the Northeast Passage above Siberia.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] At Williams Island the crew encountered a polar bear for the first time.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They managed to bring it on board, but the bear rampaged and was killed.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz reached the west coast of Novaya Zemlya and followed it northward, before being forced to turn back in the face of large icebergs.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The following year, Prince Maurice of Orange named him chief pilot of a new expedition of six ships, loaded with merchant wares that the Dutch hoped to trade with China.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The party came across Samoyed "wild men" but eventually turned back upon discovering the Kara Sea frozen.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1596, the States-General offered a high reward for anybody who *successfully* navigated the Northeast Passage.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The Town Council of Amsterdam purchased and outfitted two small ships, captained by Jan Rijp and Jacob van Heemskerck, to search for the elusive channel, under the command of Barents.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They set off in May, and in June discovered Bear Island and Spitsbergen, sighting its northwest coast.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They saw a large bay, later called Raudfjorden and entered Magdalenefjorden, which they named *Tusk Bay*, sailing into the northern entrance of Forlandsundet, which they called *Keerwyck*, but were forced to turn back because of a shoal.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 28 June they rounded the northern point of Prins Karls Forland, which they named *Vogelhoek*, on account of a large number of birds, and sailed south, passing Isfjorden and Bellsund, which were labelled on Barentsz's chart as *Grooten Inwyck* and *Inwyck*.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The ships once again reached Bear Island on 1 July, which led to a disagreement.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They parted ways, with Barentsz continuing northeast, while Rijp headed north.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz reached Novaya Zemlya and, to avoid becoming entrapped in ice, headed for the Kara Strait but became stuck within the icebergs and floes.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Stranded, the 16-man crew was forced to spend the winter on the ice.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The crew used lumber from their ship to build a lodge they called *Het Behouden Huys* (The Kept House).
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Dealing with extreme cold, they used merchant fabrics to make additional blankets and clothing and caught Arctic foxes in primitive traps, as well as polar bears.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] When June arrived, and the ice had still not loosened its grip on the ship, scurvy-ridden survivors took two small boats out into the sea.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz died at sea on 20 June 1597, while studying charts.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] It took seven more weeks for the boats to reach Kola where they were rescued by a Russian merchant vessel.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Only 12 crewmen remained, reaching Amsterdam in November.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Two of Barentsz' crewmembers later published their journals, Jan Huyghen van Linschoten, who had accompanied him on the first two voyages, and Gerrit de Veer who had acted as the ship's carpenter on the last.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Juan Fernández, sailing from Chile in 1576, claimed he had discovered the Southern Continent.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Luís Vaz de Torres, a Galician navigator working for the Spanish Crown, proved the existence of a passage south of New Guinea, now known as Torres Strait.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Pedro Fernandes de Queirós, a Portuguese navigator sailing for the Spanish Crown, saw a large island south of New Guinea in 1606, which he named *Austrialia del Espiritu Santo* (transl.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Southern-Austrian Land of the Holy Spirit).
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] He represented this to the King of Spain as the *Terra Australis incognita*, but it was present-day Vanuatu rather than Australia or Antarctica.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch navigator and colonial governor, Willem Janszoon sailed from the Netherlands for the East Indies for the third time on 18 December 1603, as captain of *Duyfken* (or *Duijfken*, meaning 'Little Dove'), one of twelve ships of the great fleet of Steven van der Hagen.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Once in the Indies, Janszoon was sent to search for other outlets of trade, particularly in "the great land of Nova Guinea and other East and Southlands".
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 18 November 1605, *Duyfken* sailed from Banten to the coast of western New Guinea.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Janszoon then crossed the eastern end of the Arafura Sea, without becoming aware of the Torres Strait, into the Gulf of Carpentaria.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 26 February 1606, he made landfall at the Pennefather River on the western shore of Cape York in Queensland, near the modern town of Weipa.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] This is the first recorded European landfall on the Australian continent.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Janszoon proceeded to chart some 320 kilometres (199 mi) of the coastline, which he thought was a southerly extension of New Guinea.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1615, Jacob Le Maire and Willem Schouten's rounding of Cape Horn proved that Tierra del Fuego was a relatively small island.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1642 to 1644, Abel Tasman, also a Dutch explorer and merchant in the service of the VOC, circumnavigated New Holland proving that Australia was not part of the mythical southern continent.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] He was the first known European expedition to reach the islands of Van Diemen's Land (now Tasmania) and New Zealand and to sight the Fiji islands, which he did in 1643.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Tasman, his navigator Visscher, and his merchant Gilsemans also mapped substantial portions of Australia, New Zealand, and the Pacific islands.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In the mid-16th century, the Tsardom of Russia conquered the Tatar khanates of Kazan and Astrakhan, thus annexing the entire Volga region and opening the way to the Ural Mountains.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The colonization of the new easternmost lands of Russia and further onslaught eastward was led by the rich merchants Stroganovs.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Ivan the Terrible granted vast estates near the Urals as well as tax privileges to Anikey Stroganov, who organized large-scale migration to these lands.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The Stroganovs developed farming, hunting, saltworks, fishing, and ore mining on the Urals and established trade with Siberian tribes.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Around 1577, Semyon Stroganov and other sons of Anikey Stroganov hired a Cossack leader called Yermak to protect their lands from the attacks of Khan Kuchum.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1580, Stroganovs and Yermak came up with the idea of a military expedition to Siberia, to fight Kuchum in his own land.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1581, Yermak began his voyage into the depths of Siberia.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] After a few victories over the Khan's army, Yermak's people defeated the main forces of Kuchum on Irtysh River in the three-day Battle of Chuvash Cape in 1582.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The remains of the Khan's army retreated to the steppes, and thus Yermak captured the Khanate of Sibir, including its capital Qashliq near modern Tobolsk.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Kuchum still was strong and suddenly attacked Yermak in 1585 in the dead of night, killing most of his people.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Yermak was wounded and tried to swim across the Wagay River (Irtysh's tributary), but drowned under the weight of his own chain mail.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The Cossacks had to withdraw from Siberia completely, but thanks to Yermak's having explored all the main river routes in West Siberia, Russians successfully reclaimed all his conquests just several years later.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In the early 17th century, the eastward movement of Russians was slowed by the internal problems in the country during the Time of Troubles.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Very soon, exploration and colonization of the huge territories of Siberia resumed, led mostly by Cossacks hunting for valuable furs and ivory.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] While Cossacks came from the Southern Urals, another wave of Russians came by the Arctic Ocean.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] These were Pomors from the Russian North, who already had been making fur trade with Mangazeya in the north of Western Siberia for quite a long time.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1607, the settlement of Turukhansk was founded on the northern Yenisey River, near the mouth of Lower Tunguska.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1619, Yeniseysk ostrog was founded on the mid-Yenisey at the mouth of the Upper Tunguska.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Between 1620 and 1624, a group of fur hunters led by Demid Pyanda left Turukhansk and explored some 1,430 miles (2,300 kilometres) of the Lower Tunguska, wintering in the proximity of the Vilyuy and Lena Rivers.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] According to later legendary accounts (folktales collected a century after the fact), Pyanda discovered the Lena.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] He allegedly explored some 1,500 miles (2,400 kilometres) of its length, reaching as far as central Yakutia.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] He returned up the Lena until it became too rocky and shallow, and portaged to the Angara River.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In this way, Pyanda may have become the first Russian to meet Yakuts and Buryats.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] He built new boats and explored some 870 miles (1,400 kilometres) of the Angara, finally reaching Yeniseysk and discovering that the Angara (a Buryat name) and Upper Tunguska (Verkhnyaya Tunguska, as initially known by Russians) are one and the same river.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1627, Pyotr Beketov was appointed Yenisei voevoda in Siberia.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] He successfully carried out the voyage to collect taxes from the Zabaykalye Buryats, becoming the first Russian to step in Buryatia.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] He founded the first Russian settlement there, Rybinsky ostrog.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Beketov was sent to the Lena River in 1631, where in 1632 he founded Yakutsk and sent his Cossacks to explore the Aldan River and farther down the Lena, to found new fortresses, and to collect taxes.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Yakutsk soon turned into a major starting point for further Russian expeditions eastward, southward and northward.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Maksim Perfilyev, who earlier had been one of the founders of Yeniseysk, founded Bratsk ostrog on the Angara in 1631.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1638, Perfilyev became the first Russian to step into Transbaikalia, travelling there from Yakutsk.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1643, Kurbat Ivanov led a group of Cossacks from Yakutsk to the south of the Baikal Mountains and discovered Lake Baikal, visiting its Olkhon Island.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Ivanov later made the first chart and description of Baikal.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1639, a group of explorers led by Ivan Moskvitin became the first Russians to reach the Pacific Ocean and to discover the Sea of Okhotsk, having built a winter camp on its shore at the Ulya River mouth.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The Cossacks learned from the locals about the large Amur River far to the south.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1640, they apparently sailed south, and explored the south-eastern shores of the Okhotsk Sea, perhaps reaching the mouth of the Amur River and possibly discovering the Shantar Islands on their way back.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Based on Moskvitin's account, Kurbat Ivanov drew the first Russian map of the Far East in 1642.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1643, Vassili Poyarkov crossed the Stanovoy Range and reached the upper Zeya River in the country of the Daurs, who were paying tribute to the Manchus.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] After wintering, in 1644, Poyarkov pushed down the Zeya and became the first Russian to reach the Amur River.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] He sailed down the Amur and finally discovered the mouth of that great river from land.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Since his Cossacks provoked the enmity of the locals behind, Poyarkov chose a different way back.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] They built boats and in 1645, sailed along the Sea of Okhotsk coast to the Ulya River and spent the next winter in the huts that had been built by Ivan Moskvitin six years earlier.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1644, Mikhail Stadukhin discovered the Kolyma River and founded Srednekolymsk.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] A merchant named Fedot Alekseyevich Popov organized a further expedition eastward, and Semyon Dezhnyov became a captain of one of the kochi.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1648, they sailed from Srednekolymsk down to the Arctic and after some time they rounded Cape Dezhnyov, thus becoming the first explorers to pass through the Bering Strait and discover Chukotka and the Bering Sea.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] All their Kochi and most of their men (including Popov himself) were lost in storms and clashes with the natives.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] A small group led by Dezhnyov reached the mouth of the Anadyr River and sailed up it in 1649, having built new boats from the wreckage.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] They founded Anadyrsk and were stranded there until Stadukhin found them, coming from Kolyma by land.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Subsequently, Stadukhin set off south in 1651 and discovered Penzhin Bay on the northern coast of the Okhotsk Sea.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] He also may have explored the western shores of Kamchatka.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1649 to 1650, Yerofey Khabarov became the second Russian to explore the Amur River.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Through the Olyokma, Tungir, and Shilka Rivers he reached Amur (Dauriya), returned to Yakutsk and then back to Amur with a larger force in 1650–1653.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] This time he was met with armed resistance.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] He built winter quarters at Albazin, then sailed down Amur and found Achansk, which preceded the present-day Khabarovsk, defeating or evading large armies of Daurs, Manchus, Chinese, and Koreans on his way.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] He charted the Amur in his *Draft of the Amur river*.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Subsequently, the Russians held on to the Amur region until 1689, when by the Treaty of Nerchinsk this land was assigned to the Qing Empire.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] It was returned by the Treaty of Aigun in 1858.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1659 to 1665, Kurbat Ivanov was the next head of Anadyrsky ostrog after Semyon Dezhnev.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1660, he sailed from Anadyr Bay to Cape Dezhnyov.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] By the mid-17th century, the Russians established the borders of their country close to modern ones, and explored almost the whole of Siberia, except the eastern Kamchatka and some regions north of the Arctic Circle.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The conquest of Kamchatka later would be achieved in the early 1700s by Vladimir Atlasov, while the discovery of the Arctic coastline and Alaska would be completed by the Great Northern Expedition in 1733–1743.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] European overseas expansion led to contact between the Old and New Worlds producing the Columbian exchange.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] It started the global silver trade between the Americas, Europe, and China, and led to direct European involvement in the Chinese porcelain trade.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] It involved the transfer of goods unique from one hemisphere to another.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] From the Old World, Europeans brought cattle, horses, and sheep to the New World, and from the New World Europeans received tobacco, potatoes, tomatoes, and maize.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Other items and commodities becoming important in global trade were the tobacco, sugarcane, and cotton crops of the Americas, along with the gold and silver brought from the American continent not only to Europe, but elsewhere in the Old World.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The formation of new transoceanic links and expansion of European influence led to the Age of Imperialism, which began during the Age of Discovery, during which colonial powers from Europe colonized most territory on the planet.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Combined with the introduction of infectious diseases from Europe, these events led to a drastic decrease of the American Indian population.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] American Indian accounts of European colonization were summarized by scholar Peter Mancall: "The arrival of Europeans brought death, displacement, sorrow, and despair to Native Americans".
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In some areas, like North America, Central America, Australia, New Zealand, and Argentina, indigenous peoples were poorly treated, driven off their lands, and reduced to dependent minorities in the territory.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Similarly, in East and West Africa, local states supplied the appetite of European slave traders, changing the complexion of coastal African states and fundamentally altering the nature of slavery in Africa, causing impacts on societies and economies deep inland.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In North America, there were many conflicts between European colonists and American Indians.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Maize and manioc were introduced into Africa in the 16th century by the Portuguese.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] They are now important staple foods, replacing native African crops.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Crosby speculated that increased production of maize, manioc, and other New World crops led to heavier concentrations of population in the areas from which slavers captured their victims.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In the global silver trade, China was stimulated by trade with the Portuguese, Spaniards, and Dutch.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Although global, much of that silver ended up with the Chinese, and China dominated silver imports.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Between 1600 and 1800, China received 100 tons of silver on average per year.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] A large populace near the Lower Yangtze averaged hundreds of taels of silver per household in the late 16th century.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] More than 150,000 tons of silver were shipped from Potosí by the end of the 18th century.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1500 to 1800, Mexico and Peru produced about 80% of the world's silver, with more than 30% of it eventually ending up in China (largely because European merchants used it to purchase exotic Chinese commodities).
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In the late 16th and early 17th century, Japan was exporting heavily into China and foreign trade at large.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Trade with European powers and the Japanese brought in significant amounts of silver, which then replaced copper and paper banknotes as the common medium of exchange in China.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] During the last decades of the Ming dynasty, the flow of silver into China was greatly diminished, thereby undermining state revenues and the entire Ming economy.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] This damage to the economy was compounded by the effects on agriculture of the incipient Little Ice Age, natural calamities, crop failure, and sudden epidemics.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The ensuing breakdown of authority and people's livelihoods allowed rebel leaders such as Li Zicheng to challenge Ming authority.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] New crops that had come to Asia from the Americas, via the Spanish colonizers in the 16th century, contributed to Asia's population growth.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Although the bulk of imports to China were silver, the Chinese also purchased New World crops from the Spanish Empire.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] This included sweet potatoes, maize, and peanuts, foods that could be cultivated in lands where traditional Chinese staple crops—wheat, millet, and rice—could not grow, hence facilitating a rise in the population of China.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In the Song dynasty (960–1279), rice had become the major staple crop of the poor; after sweet potatoes were introduced to China around 1560, it gradually became the traditional food of the lower classes.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The arrival of the Portuguese to Japan in 1543 initiated the Nanban trade period, with the Japanese adopting technologies and cultural practices, like the arquebus, European-style cuirasses, European ships, Christianity, decorative art, and language.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] After the Chinese had banned direct trade by Chinese merchants with Japan, the Portuguese filled this commercial vacuum as intermediaries.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The Portuguese bought Chinese silk and sold it to the Japanese in return for Japanese-mined silver; since silver was more highly valued in China, the Portuguese could then use Japanese silver to buy even larger stocks of Chinese silk.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1573, after the Spaniards established a trading base in Manila, the Portuguese intermediary trade was trumped by the prime source of incoming silver to China from the Spanish Americas.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Although China acted as the cog running the wheel of global trade during the 16th to 18th centuries, Japan's huge contribution of silver exports to China was critical to the world economy and China's liquidity and success with the commodity.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] As a wider variety of global luxury commodities entered the European markets by sea, previous European markets for luxury goods stagnated.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The Atlantic trade largely supplanted pre-existing Italian and German trading powers which had relied on their Baltic, Russian, and Islamic trade links.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The new commodities also caused social change, as sugar, spices, silks, and chinawares entered the luxury markets of Europe.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The European economic centre shifted from the Mediterranean to Western Europe.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The city of Antwerp, part of the Duchy of Brabant, became "the centre of the *entire* international economy", and the richest city in Europe.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Centred in Antwerp first and then Amsterdam, the Dutch Golden Age was tightly linked to the Age of Discovery.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1549, the Portuguese empire sent annual trade missions to Shangchuan Island in China.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1557, they managed to convince the Ming court to agree on a legal port treaty that would establish Macau as an official Portuguese trade colony.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] From China, the major exports were silk and porcelain, adapted to meet European tastes.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The Chinese export porcelains were held in such great esteem in Europe that, in English, *china* became a commonly used synonym for *porcelain*.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Kraak porcelain was among the first Chinese ware to arrive in Europe in significant quantities; only the richest could afford these early imports.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Soon the Dutch East India Company established trade with the East, having imported 6 million porcelain items from China to Europe between 1602 and 1682.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Kraak, mainly the blue and white porcelain, was imitated all over the world by potters in Arita, Japan and Persia—where Dutch merchants turned when the fall of the Ming dynasty rendered Chinese originals unavailable—and ultimately in delftware.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Dutch and later English delftware inspired by Chinese designs persisted from about 1630 to the mid-18th century alongside European patterns.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Antonio de Morga (1559–1636), a Spanish official in Manila, listed an extensive inventory of goods that were traded by Ming China at the turn of the 16th to 17th century, noting there were "rarities which, did I refer to them all, I would never finish, nor have sufficient paper for it".
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Ebrey writes of the considerable size of commercial transactions: In one case a galleon to the Spanish territories in the New World carried over 50,000 pairs of silk stockings.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In return China imported mostly silver from Peruvian and Mexican mines, transported via Manila.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Chinese merchants were active in these trading ventures, and many emigrated to such places as the Philippines and Borneo to take advantage of the new commercial opportunities.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The increase in gold and silver experienced by Spain coincided with a major inflationary cycle within Spain and Europe, known as the price revolution.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Spain had amassed large quantities of gold and silver from the New World.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In the 1540s, large scale extraction of silver from Mexico began.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] During the 16th century, Spain held the equivalent of US$1.5 trillion (1990 terms) in gold and silver from New Spain.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Being the most powerful European monarch at a time full of war and religious conflicts, the Habsburg rulers spent their wealth in wars and arts across Europe.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The spent silver, spread throughout a cash-starved Europe, caused widespread inflation.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The inflation was worsened by a growing population with a static production level, low salaries and a rising cost of living, which damaged local industry.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Increasingly, Spain became dependent on the revenues flowing in from the mercantile empire, leading to Spain's first bankruptcy in 1557 due to rising military costs.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Philip II of Spain defaulted on debt payments in 1557, 1560, 1575, and 1596.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The increase in prices as a result of currency circulation fuelled the growth of the commercial middle class in Europe, the *bourgeoisie*, which came to influence the politics and culture of many countries.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] One effect of the inflation, particularly in Great Britain, was that tenant farmers who held long-term leases from lords saw real decreases in rent.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Some lords opted to sell their leased land, giving rise to small, landowning farmers.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] The **Age of Sail** is the period in European history from the mid-15th or 16th century to, at the latest, the mid-19th century, in which the dominance of sailing ships in global trade and warfare culminated.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] Marked by the introduction of naval artillery, the Age of Sail ultimately reached its highest extent at the advent of steam power.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] Enabled by the advances of the related age of navigation, it is identified as a distinctive element of the early modern period and the Age of Discovery.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] Like most periodic eras, defining the age is inexact and serves only as a general description.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] The term is used differently for warships and merchant vessels.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] By the 14th century naval artillery was employed in Europe, documented at the Battle of Arnemuiden (1338).
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] The 15th century saw the Iberian naval ventures all the way along the African Atlantic coast and across the Atlantic Ocean, starting the Age of Discovery.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] For warships, the age of sail runs roughly from the Battle of Lepanto in 1571, the last significant engagement in which oar-propelled galleys played a major role, to the development of steam-powered warships.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] The period between the mid-19th century to the early 20th century, when sailing vessels reached their peak of size and complexity (e.g. clippers and windjammers), is sometimes referred to as the "Golden Age of Sail".
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] The second sea-going steamboat was Richard Wright's first steamboat *Experiment*, an ex-French lugger; she steamed from Leeds to Yarmouth in July 1813.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] The first iron steamship to go to sea was the 116-ton *Aaron Manby*, built in 1821 by Aaron Manby at the Horseley Ironworks, and became the first iron-built vessel to put to sea when she crossed the English Channel in 1822, arriving in Paris on 22 June.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] She carried passengers and freight to Paris in 1822 at an average speed of 8 knots (9.2 mph; 15 km/h).
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] The first purpose-built steam battleship was the 90-gun *Napoléon* in 1850.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] Multiple steam battleships saw action during the Crimean War, especially the Allied (British, French and Ottoman) fleet Bombardment of Sevastopol as part of the Siege of Sevastopol (1854–1855).
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] The first ironclad battleship, *Gloire*, was launched by the French Navy in November 1859.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] In the March 1862 Battle of Hampton Roads, the ironclad CSS *Virginia* fought USS *Monitor*, making this the first fight between ironclads.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] The Suez Canal in the Middle East, which opened in 1869, was more practical for steamships than for sailing ships, achieving a much shorter European-Asian sea route, which coincided with more fuel-efficient steamships, starting with *Agamemnon* in 1865.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] HMS *Devastation*, the first class of ocean-going battleships that did not carry sails, was commissioned in 1871.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] Sailing ships continued to be an economical way to transport bulk cargo on long voyages into the 1920s and 1930s, though steamships soon pushed them out of those trades as well.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] Sailing ships do not require fuel or complex engines to be powered; thus they tended to be more independent from sophisticated dedicated support bases on land.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] Crucially though, steam-powered ships held a speed advantage and were rarely hindered by adverse winds, freeing steam-powered vessels from the necessity of following trade winds.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] As a result, cargo and supplies could reach a foreign port in a fraction of the time it took a sailing ship.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] Sailing vessels were pushed into narrower and narrower economic niches and gradually disappeared from commercial trade.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] Today, sailing vessels are only economically viable for small-scale coastal fishing, along with recreational uses such as yachting and passenger sail excursion ships.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] In recent decades, the commercial shipping industry has been reviving interest in wind assisted ships as a way to conserve fuel in the interest of sustainability.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] A **New Age of Sail** has been predicted by some experts to occur by 2030, driven by a revolution in energy technology and a desire to reduce carbon emissions from maritime shipping through wind-assisted propulsion.
[src:sailing-ship/age-of-sail] The book *Trade Winds: A Voyage to a Sustainable Future for Shipping* discusses the potential of a return to wind propulsion through the firsthand experiences of Christiaan De Beukelaer, who spent five months aboard a sailing cargo ship in 2020.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Showing three-masted examples, progressing from square sails on each to all fore-and-aft sails on each.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] A **sailing ship** is a sea-going vessel that uses sails mounted on masts to harness the power of wind and propel the vessel.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] There is a variety of sail plans that propel sailing ships, employing square-rigged or fore-and-aft sails.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Some ships carry square sails on each mast—the brig and full-rigged ship, said to be "ship-rigged" when there are three or more masts.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Others carry only fore-and-aft sails on each mast, for instance some schooners.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Still others employ a combination of square and fore-and-aft sails, including the barque, barquentine, and brigantine.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Early sailing ships were used for river and coastal waters in ancient Egypt and the Mediterranean.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The Austronesian peoples developed maritime technologies that included the fore-and-aft crab-claw sail and with catamaran and outrigger hull configurations, which enabled the Austronesian expansion into the islands of the Indo-Pacific.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] 3000 BC and propagated through Island Southeast Asia, reaching Near Oceania c.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The maritime trading network in the Indo-Pacific dates from at least 1500 BC.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Later developments in Asia produced the junk and dhow—vessels that incorporated features unknown in Europe at the time.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] European sailing ships with predominantly square rigs became prevalent during the Age of Discovery (15th to 17th centuries), when they crossed oceans between continents and around the world.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] In the European Age of Sail, a full-rigged ship was one with a bowsprit and three masts, each of which consists of a lower, top, and topgallant mast.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Most sailing ships were merchantmen, but the Age of Sail also saw the development of large fleets of well-armed warships.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The many steps of technological development of steamships during the 19th century provided slowly increasing competition for sailing ships—initially only on short routes where high prices could be charged.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] By the 1880s, ships with triple-expansion steam engines had the fuel efficiency to compete with sail on all major routes—and with scheduled sailings that were not affected by the wind direction.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] However, commercial sailing vessels could still be found working into the 20th century, although in reducing numbers and only in certain trades.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] By the Age of Discovery—starting in the 15th century—square-rigged, multi-masted vessels were the norm and were guided by navigation techniques that included the magnetic compass and making sightings of the sun and stars that allowed transoceanic voyages.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The Age of Sail reached its peak in the 18th and 19th centuries with large, heavily armed battleships and merchant sailing ships.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Sailing and steam ships coexisted for much of the 19th century.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The steamers of the early part of the century had very poor fuel efficiency and were suitable only for a small number of roles, such as towing sailing ships and providing short route passenger and mail services.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Both sailing and steam ships saw large technological improvements over the century.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Ultimately the two large stepwise improvements in fuel efficiency of compound and then triple-expansion steam engines made the steamship, by the 1880s, able to compete in the vast majority of trades.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Commercial sail still continued into the 20th century, with the last ceasing to trade by c.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Early sea-going sailing vessels were used by the Austronesian peoples.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The invention of catamarans, outriggers, and crab claw sails enabled the Austronesian Expansion at around 3000 to 1500 BC.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] From Taiwan, they rapidly colonized the islands of Maritime Southeast Asia, then sailed further onwards to Micronesia, Island Melanesia, Polynesia, and Madagascar.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Austronesian rigs were distinctive in that they had spars supporting both the upper and lower edges of the sails (and sometimes in between), in contrast to western rigs which only had a spar on the upper edge.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Large Austronesian trading ships with as many as four sails were recorded by Han dynasty (206 BC – 220 AD) scholars as the *kunlun bo* or *K'un-lun po* (崑崙舶, lit.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] They were booked by Chinese Buddhist pilgrims for passage to Southern India and Sri Lanka.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Bas reliefs of large Javanese outriggers ships with various configurations of tanja sails are also found in the Borobudur temple, dating back to the 8th century CE.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] By the 10th century AD, the Song dynasty started building the first Chinese seafaring junks, which adopted several features of the *K'un-lun po*.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The junk rig in particular, became associated with Chinese coast-hugging trading ships.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Junks in China were constructed from teak with pegs and nails; they featured watertight compartments and acquired center-mounted tillers and rudders.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] These ships became the basis for the development of Chinese warships during the Mongol Yuan dynasty, and were used in the unsuccessful Mongol invasions of Japan and Java.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The Ming dynasty (1368–1644) saw the use of junks as long-distance trading vessels.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Chinese Admiral Zheng He reportedly sailed to India, Arabia, and southern Africa on a trade and diplomatic mission.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Literary lore suggests that his largest vessel, the "Treasure Ship", measured 400 feet (120 m) in length and 150 feet (46 m) in width, whereas modern research suggests that it was unlikely to have exceeded 70 metres (230 ft) in length.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Sailing ships in the Mediterranean region date back to at least 3000 BC, when Egyptians used a bipod mast to support a single square sail on a vessel that mainly relied on multiple paddlers.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Later the mast became a single pole, and paddles were supplanted with oars.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Such vessels plied both the Nile and the Mediterranean coast.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The Minoan civilization of Crete may have been the world's first thalassocracy brought to prominence by sailing vessels dating to before 1800 BC (Middle Minoan IIB).
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Between 1000 BC and 400 AD, the Phoenicians, Greeks and Romans developed ships that were powered by square sails, sometimes with oars to supplement their capabilities.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Such vessels used a steering oar as a rudder to control direction.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Starting in the 8th century in Denmark, Vikings were building clinker-constructed longships propelled by a single, square sail, when practical, and oars, when necessary.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] A related craft was the knarr, which plied the Baltic and North Seas, using primarily sail power.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The windward edge of the sail was stiffened with a beitass, a pole that fitted into the lower corner of the sail, when sailing close to the wind.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] India's maritime history began during the 3rd millennium BCE when inhabitants of the Indus Valley initiated maritime trading contact with Mesopotamia.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Indian kingdoms such as the Kalinga from as early as 2nd century CE are believed to have had sailing ships.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] One of the earliest instances of documented evidence of Indian sailing ship building comes from the mural of three-masted ship in the Ajanta caves that date back to 400-500 CE.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The Indian Ocean was the venue for increasing trade between India and Africa between 1200 and 1500.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The vessels employed would be classified as dhows with lateen rigs.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] During this interval such vessels grew in capacity from 100 to 400 tonnes.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Dhows were often built with teak planks from India and Southeast Asia, sewn together with coconut husk fiber—no nails were employed.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] This period also saw the implementation of center-mounted rudders, controlled with a tiller.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Technological advancements that were important to the Age of Discovery in the 15th century were the adoption of the magnetic compass and advances in ship design.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] It had been used for navigation in China by the 11th century and was adopted by the Arab traders in the Indian Ocean.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] At the beginning of the 15th century, the carrack was the most capable European ocean-going ship.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] It was carvel-built and large enough to be stable in heavy seas.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] It was capable of carrying a large cargo and the provisions needed for very long voyages.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Later carracks were square-rigged on the foremast and mainmast and lateen-rigged on the mizzenmast.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] They had a high rounded stern with large aftcastle, forecastle and bowsprit at the stem.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] As the predecessor of the galleon, the carrack was one of the most influential ship designs in history; while ships became more specialized in the following centuries, the basic design remained unchanged throughout this period.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Ships of this era were only able to sail approximately 70° into the wind and tacked from one side to the other across the wind with difficulty, which made it challenging to avoid shipwrecks when near shores or shoals during storms.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Nonetheless, such vessels reached India around Africa with Vasco da Gama, the Americas with Christopher Columbus, and around the world under Ferdinand Magellan.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Sailing ships became longer and faster over time, with ship-rigged vessels carrying taller masts with more square sails.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Other sail plans emerged, as well, that had just fore-and-aft sails (schooners), or a mixture of the two (brigantines, barques and barquentines).
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Cannons were introduced in the 14th century, but did not become common at sea until they could be reloaded quickly enough to be reused in the same battle.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The size of a ship required to carry a large number of cannon made oar-based propulsion impossible, and warships came to rely primarily on sails.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The sailing man-of-war emerged during the 16th century.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] By the middle of the 17th century, warships were carrying increasing numbers of cannon on three decks.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Naval tactics evolved to bring each ship's firepower to bear in a line of battle—coordinated movements of a fleet of warships to engage a line of ships in the enemy fleet.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Carracks with a single cannon deck evolved into galleons with as many as two full cannon decks, which evolved into the man-of-war, and further into the ship of the line—designed for engaging the enemy in a line of battle.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] One side of a ship was expected to shoot broadsides against an enemy ship at close range.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] In the 18th century, the small and fast frigate and sloop-of-war—too small to stand in the line of battle—evolved to convoy trade, scout for enemy ships and blockade enemy coasts.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The term "clipper" started to be used in the first quarter of the 19th century.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] It was applied to sailing vessels designed primarily for speed.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Only a small proportion of sailing vessels could properly have the term applied to them.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Early examples were the schooners and brigantines, called Baltimore clippers, used for blockade running or as privateers in the War of 1812 and afterwards for smuggling opium or illegally transporting slaves.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Larger clippers, usually ship or barque rigged and with a different hull design, were built for the California trade (from east coast USA ports to San Francisco) after gold was discovered in 1848 – the associated shipbuilding boom lasted until 1854.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Clippers were built for trade between the United Kingdom and China after the East India Company lost its monopoly in 1834.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The primary cargo was tea, and sailing ships, particularly tea clippers, dominated this long-distance route until the development of fuel efficient steamships coincided with the opening of the Suez Canal in 1869.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Other clippers worked on the Australian immigrant routes or, in smaller quantities, in any role where a fast passage secured higher rates of freight or passenger fares.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Whilst many clippers were ship rigged, the definition is not limited to any rig.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Clippers were generally built for a specific trade: those in the California trade had to withstand the seas of Cape Horn, whilst Tea Clippers were designed for the lighter and contrary winds of the China Sea.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] All had fine lines, with a well streamlined hull and carried a large sail area.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] To get the best of this, a skilled and determined master was needed in command.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] During the Age of Sail, ships' hulls were under frequent attack by shipworm (which affected the structural strength of timbers), and barnacles and various marine weeds (which affected ship speed).
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Since before the common era, a variety of coatings had been applied to hulls to counter this effect, including pitch, wax, tar, oil, sulfur and arsenic.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] In the mid 18th century copper sheathing was developed as a defense against such bottom fouling.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] After coping with problems of galvanic deterioration of metal hull fasteners, sacrificial anodes were developed, which were designed to corrode, instead of the hull fasteners.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The practice became widespread on naval vessels, starting in the late 18th century, and on merchant vessels, starting in the early 19th century, until the advent of iron and steel hulls.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Iron-hulled sailing ships, often referred to as "windjammers" or "tall ships", represented the final evolution of sailing ships at the end of the Age of Sail.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] They were built to carry bulk cargo for long distances in the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] They were the largest of merchant sailing ships, with three to five masts and square sails, as well as other sail plans.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] They carried lumber, guano, grain or ore between continents.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Iron-hulled sailing ships were mainly built from the 1870s to 1900, when steamships began to outpace them economically, due to their ability to keep a schedule regardless of the wind.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Steel hulls also replaced iron hulls at around the same time.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Even into the twentieth century, sailing ships could hold their own on transoceanic voyages such as Australia to Europe, since they did not require bunkerage for coal nor fresh water for steam, and they were faster than the early steamers, which usually could barely make 8 knots (15 km/h).
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The four-masted, iron-hulled ship, introduced in 1875 with the full-rigged *County of Peebles*, represented an especially efficient configuration that prolonged the competitiveness of sail against steam in the later part of the 19th century.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The largest example of such ships was the five-masted, full-rigged ship *Preussen*, which had a load capacity of 7,800 tonnes.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Ships transitioned from all sail to all steam-power from the mid 19th century into the 20th.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Five-masted *Preussen* used steam power for driving the winches, hoists and pumps, and could be manned by a crew of 48, compared with four-masted *Kruzenshtern*, which has a crew of 257.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Coastal top-sail schooners with a crew as small as two managing the sail handling became an efficient way to carry bulk cargo, since only the fore-sails required tending while tacking and steam-driven machinery was often available for raising the sails and the anchor.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] In the 20th century, the DynaRig allowed central, automated control of all sails in a manner that obviates the need for sending crew aloft.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] This was developed in the 1960s in Germany as a low-carbon footprint propulsion alternative for commercial ships.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The rig automatically sets and reefs sails; its mast rotates to align the sails with the wind.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The sailing yachts *Maltese Falcon* and *Black Pearl* employ the rig.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] In the 21st century, due to concern about climate change and the possibility of cost savings, companies explored using wind-power to reduce heavy fuel needs on large containerized cargo ships.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] By 2023, around 30 ships were using sails or attached kites, with the number expected to grow.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The following year, *The Economist* wrote that the technology was at an inflection point as it moved from trials and testing towards adoption by the industry.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Every sailing ship has a sail plan that is adapted to the purpose of the vessel and the ability of the crew; each has a hull, rigging and masts to hold up the sails that use the wind to power the ship; the masts are supported by standing rigging and the sails are adjusted by running rigging.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Hull shapes for sailing ships evolved from being relatively short and blunt to being longer and finer at the bow.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] By the nineteenth century, ships were built with reference to a half model, made from wooden layers that were pinned together.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Each layer could be scaled to the actual size of the vessel in order to lay out its hull structure, starting with the keel and leading to the ship's ribs.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The ribs were pieced together from curved elements, called futtocks and tied in place until the installation of the planking.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Typically, planking was caulked with a tar-impregnated yarn made from manila or hemp to make the planking watertight.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Starting in the mid-19th century, iron was used first for the hull structure and later for its watertight sheathing.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Until the mid-19th century all vessels' masts were made of wood formed from a single or several pieces of timber which typically consisted of the trunk of a conifer tree.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] From the 16th century, vessels were often built of a size requiring masts taller and thicker than could be made from single tree trunks.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] On these larger vessels, to achieve the required height, the masts were built from up to four sections (also called masts), known in order of rising height above the decks as the lower, top, topgallant and royal masts.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Giving the lower sections sufficient thickness necessitated building them up from separate pieces of wood.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Such a section was known as a *made mast*, as opposed to sections formed from single pieces of timber, which were known as *pole masts*.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Starting in the second half of the 19th century, masts were made of iron or steel.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Each rig is configured in a *sail plan*, appropriate to the size of the sailing craft.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Both square-rigged and fore-and-aft rigged vessels have been built with a wide range of configurations for single and multiple masts.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Sailing ships have *standing rigging* to support the masts and *running rigging* to raise the sails and control their ability to draw power from the wind.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The running rigging has three main roles, to support the sail structure, to shape the sail and to adjust its angle to the wind.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Square-rigged vessels require more controlling lines than fore-and-aft rigged ones.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Sailing ships prior to the mid-19th century used wood masts with hemp-fiber standing rigging.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] As rigs became taller by the end of the 19th century, masts relied more heavily on successive spars, stepped one atop the other to form the whole, from bottom to top: the *lower mast*, *top mast*, and *topgallant mast*.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] This construction relied heavily on support by a complex array of stays and shrouds.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Each stay in either the fore-and-aft or athwartships direction had a corresponding one in the opposite direction providing counter-tension.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Fore-and-aft the system of tensioning started with the stays that were anchored in front each mast.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Shrouds were tensioned by pairs of deadeyes, circular blocks that had the large-diameter line run around them, whilst multiple holes allowed smaller line—*lanyard*—to pass multiple times between the two and thereby allow tensioning of the shroud.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] After the mid-19th century square-rigged vessels were equipped with iron wire standing rigging, which was superseded with steel wire in the late 19th century.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Halyards, used to raise and lower the yards, are the primary supporting lines.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] In addition, square rigs have lines that lift the sail or the yard from which it is suspended that include: brails, buntlines, lifts and leechlines.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Bowlines and clew lines shape a square sail.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] To adjust the angle of the sail to wind braces are used to adjust the fore and aft angle of a yard of a square sail, while sheets attach to the clews (bottom corners) of a sail to control the sail's angle to the wind.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Sheets run aft, whereas tacks are used to haul the clew of a square sail forward.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Sailing ships needed ballast to keep the centre of gravity low and supply stability to the vessel when under sail.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Ballast in the age of sail might consist of shingle, sand, lead, iron bars or bricks.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Care had to be taken in the stowage of the ballast so that it did not move during heavy weather and endanger the ship and those aboard.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Sand ballast, for instance, had to be contained by wooden boards, or in wooden boxes, to stop it moving about.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The crew of a sailing ship is divided between officers (the captain and his subordinates) and seamen or *ordinary* *hands*.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] An able seaman was expected to "hand, reef, and steer" (handle the lines and other equipment, reef the sails, and steer the vessel).
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The crew is organized to stand watch—the oversight of the ship for a period—typically four hours each.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Richard Henry Dana Jr. and Herman Melville each had personal experience aboard sailing vessels of the 19th century.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Dana described the crew of the merchant brig, *Pilgrim*, as comprising six to eight common sailors, four specialist crew members (the steward, cook, carpenter and sailmaker), and three officers: the captain, the first mate and the second mate.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] He contrasted the American crew complement with that of other nations on whose similarly sized ships the crew might number as many as 30.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Larger merchant vessels had larger crews.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Melville described the crew complement of the frigate warship, *United States*, as about 500—including officers, enlisted personnel and 50 Marines.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The crew was divided into the starboard and larboard watches.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] He additionally named such positions as, boatswains, gunners, carpenters, coopers, painters, tinkers, stewards, cooks and various boys as functions on the man-of-war.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] 18-19th century ships of the line had a complement as high as 850.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Handling a sailing ship requires management of its sails to power—but not overpower—the ship and navigation to guide the ship, both at sea and in and out of harbors.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Key elements of sailing a ship are setting the right amount of sail to generate maximum power without endangering the ship, adjusting the sails to the wind direction on the course sailed, and changing tack to bring the wind from one side of the vessel to the other.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] A sailing ship crew manages the running rigging of each square sail.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Each sail has two sheets that control its lower corners, two braces that control the angle of the yard, two clewlines, four buntlines and two reef tackles.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] All these lines must be manned as the sail is deployed and the yard raised.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] They use a halyard to raise each yard and its sail; then they pull or ease the braces to set the angle of the yard across the vessel; they pull on sheets to haul lower corners of the sail, *clews*, out to yard below.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Under way, the crew manages *reef tackles*, *haul leeches*, *reef points*, to manage the size and angle of the sail; *bowlines* pull the leading edge of the sail (*leech*) taut when close hauled.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] When furling the sail, the crew uses *clewlines*, haul up the clews and *buntlines* to haul up the middle of sail up; when lowered, *lifts* support each yard.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] In strong winds, the crew is directed to reduce the number of sails or, alternatively, the amount of each given sail that is presented to the wind by a process called *reefing*.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] To pull the sail up, seamen on the yardarm pull on *reef tackles*, attached to *reef cringles*, to pull the sail up and secure it with lines, called *reef points*.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Dana spoke of the hardships of sail handling during high wind and rain or with ice covering the ship and its rigging.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Sailing vessels cannot sail directly into the wind.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Instead, square-riggers must sail a course that is between 60° and 70° away from the wind direction and fore-and aft vessels can typically sail no closer than 45°.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] To reach a destination, sailing vessels may have to change course and allow the wind to come from the opposite side in a procedure, called *tacking*, when the wind comes across the bow during the maneuver.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The procedure is to turn the vessel into the wind with the hind-most fore-and-aft sail (the spanker), pulled to windward to help turn the ship through the eye of the wind.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Once the ship has come about, all the sails are adjusted to align properly with the new tack.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Because square-rigger masts are more strongly braced from behind than from ahead, tacking is a dangerous procedure in strong winds; the ship may lose forward momentum (become *caught in stays*) and the rigging may fail from the wind coming from ahead.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The ship may also lose momentum at wind speeds of less than 10 knots (19 km/h).
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Under these conditions, the choice may be to *wear ship*—to turn the ship away from the wind and around 240° onto the next tack (60° off the wind).
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] A fore-and-aft rig permits the wind to flow past the sail, as the craft head through the eye of the wind.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Most rigs pivot around a stay or the mast, while this occurs.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] For a jib, the old leeward sheet is released as the craft heads through the wind and the old windward sheet is tightened as the new leeward sheet to allow the sail to draw wind.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Mainsails are often self-tending and slide on a traveler to the opposite side.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] On certain rigs, such as lateens and luggers, the sail may be partially lowered to bring it to the opposite side.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Early navigational techniques employed observations of the sun, stars, waves and birdlife.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] In the 15th century, the Chinese were using the magnetic compass to identify direction of travel.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] By the 16th century in Europe, navigational instruments included the quadrant, the astrolabe, cross staff, dividers and compass.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] By the time of the Age of Exploration these tools were being used in combination with a log to measure speed, a lead line to measure soundings, and a lookout to identify potential hazards.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Later, an accurate marine sextant became standard for determining latitude and was used with an accurate chronometer to calculate longitude.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Passage planning begins with laying out a route along a chart, which comprises a series of courses between fixes—verifiable locations that confirm the actual track of the ship on the ocean.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Once a course has been set, the person at the helm attempts to follow its direction with reference to the compass.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] The navigator notes the time and speed at each fix to estimate the arrival at the next fix, a process called dead reckoning.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] For coast-wise navigation, sightings from known landmarks or navigational aids may be used to establish fixes, a process called pilotage.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Fixes were taken with a marine sextant, which measures the distance of the celestial body above the horizon.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Given the limited maneuverability of sailing ships, it could be difficult to enter and leave harbor with the presence of a tide without coordinating arrivals with a flooding tide and departures with an ebbing tide.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] In harbor, a sailing ship stood at anchor, unless it needed to be loaded or unloaded at a dock or pier, in which case it might be warped alongside or towed by a tug.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Warping involved using a long rope (the warp) between the ship and a fixed point on the shore.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] This was pulled on by a capstan on shore, or on the ship.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] This might be a multi-stage process if the route was not simple.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] If no fixed point was available, a kedge anchor might be taken out in a ship's boat to a suitable point and the ship then pulled up to the kedge.
[src:sailing-ship/sailing-ship] Square rigged vessels could use backing and filling (of the sails) to manoeuvre in a tideway, or control could be maintained by drudging the anchor - lower the anchor until it touches the bottom so that the dragging anchor gives steerage way in the flow of the tide.
